export const WARD_BOOK_SECTIONS = [{"title": "Unconscious Patient", "keywords": ["unconscious", "patient"], "content": "\nManagement of Unconscious patient\n\nQuick Evaluation:\na  GCS, Pupils (Unequal or pinpoint - Stroke (sudden onset) esp. brainstem lesion)\na  Fever, Neck rigidity (Meningo-encephalitis/ SAH)\na  Pulse, BP (To exclude Shock which may be Hypovolemic due to AWD/Vomiting/ Bleeding or\n   Cardiogenic following AMI or Septic due Infection esp. RTI, UTI)\na  Focal neurological signs (Mouth deviation, Hemiparesis, Plantar response, seizure)\na  H/O DM, Check RBS in all patients (Bed side) to exclude - Hypoglycemia/DKA/ HHS\n\nIf patient is febrile/ Fever followed by Unconsciousness Then also consider following:\n   Travel history /Endemic zone residence for Malaria(Chittagong, Sylhet, Habiganj,\n   Durgapur, Kalmakanda, Dhubaura)\n   RTI (cough +/- sputum, chest pain, SOB, Auscultation- Features of consolidation)\n   UTI (Dysuria, Frequency of micturition, Lower Ab pain)\n   Septic Shock (Fever +/- Skin Rash, Non recordable BP or SBP <90/60mm)\n   Meningoencephalitis (Fever, Neck Rigidity, Kernig sign +ve)\n\nInvestigation for All Unconscious patient (Afebrile /Febrile):\na  All Routine:\n   o  CBC, RBS, S. Creatinine, Blood Urea & Electrolytes (including HCO3 if RBS is >15)\n   o  SGPT, Urine R/E\n   o  ECG\n   o  CXR P/A View\na  CT Scan Brain (Especially if focal neurological signs present eg mouth deviation,\n   hemiparesis, focal seizure, extensor plantar)\na  Other investigation as necessary:\n   o  Urine for keton bodies if RBS>15 mmol/l\n   o  S. Troponin-I if H/O chest pain or ECG - Ischaemia\na  If Febrile then also consider with above:\n   o  Urgent ICT for Malaria, Thick and Thin film for MP (Malarial parasite) MUST\n   o  Other investigation as necessary:\n      - Blood C/S (+/-), Urine C/S, Sputum C/S if septic shock is considered.\n      - LP & CSF study for physical, biochemical, cytological, gram and AFB stain, C/S,\n        ADA if meningoencephalitis is considered (if CT Brain normal/ no papilloedema).\n\n"}, {"title": "Unconscious Patient Treatment", "keywords": ["unconscious", "patient", "treatment"], "content": "\nTreatment of Unconscious patient without Fever\n\n- NPO/TFO\n- NG feeding (Non diabetic pt -> Revit R Milk/ Diabetic pt-> RN Diabetes Milk)\n  200 ml 2hourly 10 times daily\n- Inf. NS 1000ml (if Hypoglycaemia then Inf. 5% DNS 1000ml)\n  I/V @ 10 d/min daily\n- Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V stat & once daily\n- Inj. Omeprazole 40 mg/ Seclo 40mg\n  1 vial I/V slowly stat & 12 hourly\n- Chloramphenicol Eye drop/ SQ mycetin E/D\n  1 drop B/E 6 hrly\n- Nystatin drop/ Nystat drop\n  15 drops P/O 8 hourly\n- Continuous catheterization\n- Change posture 2 hourly\n\nPlus,\na  Treatment of underlying/precipitating cause if any (eg-stroke /metabolic like\n   hypoglycaemia/DKA or Electrolyte imbalance/ AMI, discussed these separately later)\na  Treatment of associated comorbidity eg HTN/ DM or Complication if any (eg- Aspiration\n   pneumonia, see below)\n\n* If any unconscious patient develops fever&respiratory distress after 1-2 days of unconsciousness,\n  Lungs - creps (+). This may be a case of 'Aspiration pneumonia'.\n\nThen add with ongoing management:\n- O2 inhalation\n  4L-6L / min stat and sos\n- Inj- Metronidazole 100ml/Amodis 100mg\n  1 bottle I/V stat and 8 hourly\n- Call ICU if patient is deteriorating despite O2\n\nTreatment of Unconscious pt with Fever\n\n- NPO/TFO\n- NG feeding (Non diabetic pt -> Revit R Milk/ Diabetic pt-> RN Diabetes Milk)\n  200 ml 2hourly 10 times daily\n- Inf. NS 1000ml (if Hypoglycaemia then Inf. 5%DNS 1000ml)\n  I/V @ 10 d/min daily\n- Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm / Ceftron 1 gm\n  2 vial I/V stat & once daily\n- Inj. Omeprazole 40 mg/ Seclo 40mg\n  1 vial I/V slowly stat & 12 hourly\n- Inj Paracetamol/ Napa 1 gm (Or Ace Suppository 500mg P/R Stat & 8 hourly until NG Tube\n  inserted)\n  1 bottle I/V over 15 minutes stat & 8 hourly\n- Chloramphenicol Eye drop/ SQ mycetin E/D\n  1 drop B/E 6 hrly\n- Nystatin drop/ Nystat drop\n  15 drops P/O 8 hourly\n- Continuous catheterization\n- Change posture 2 hourly\n\nPlus,\nTreatment of underlying cause:\na  If neck rigidity present/ suspected Meningoencephalitis then also add:\n   - Inj Aciclovir/ Virux 500mg (or Inj Xovir 500mg) (If history is short, symptoms usually less\n     than 10 days)\n     1 bottle I/V stat & 8 hourly\n   - Inj Dexamethasone/ Roxadex 5 mg\n     2 amp I/V stat & 6 hourly (If Pt is Diabetic then use 1 amp 6 hourly)\n   - Inj phenobarbitone/ Barbit 200mg\n     1 amp I/M stat & 12 hourly (Esp. If H/O or Risk of Seizure/ Restless)\n\na  If ICT for Malaria (+ve) or High suspicion: Give Antimalarial (I/V Artesunate or Jasoquine I/V\n   Infusion)\n\na  If Septic Shock suspected: Inj Meropenam 1gm I/V 8 Hourly& Noradrenaline (Levofed) infusion.\n\n   (Rx of Septic shock and Malaria Discussed later separately)\n\n"}, {"title": "Stroke", "keywords": ["stroke"], "content": "\n(Note:\na  If Vomiting or H/O Vomiting then also add:\n   - Inj Emistat/ Ofran 8 mg\n     1 amp I/V stat & hourly\n\na  Treatment of associated comorbidity e.g: HTN/ DM or Complication if any (e.g: Aspiration\n   pneumonia)\n\nManagement of Stroke\n\nSymptoms/ Signs:\na  Sudden Mouth deviation, Slurring of Speech, Hemiparesis, Altered consciousness, Focal Seizure.\na  GCS, Pupils (may be unequal or pinpoint), Plantar- Extensor\na  Check Bedside RBS if altered consciousness/ unconsciousness\n\nQuick Assessment for etiology:\na  H/O DM, HTN, Previous CVD, IHD/ Heart problem/ Medicine for Heart problem esp.\n   Ecosprin/Carva, Warfarin.\na  Pulse rhythm/regularity: Irregular pulse/ Atrial fibrillation.\na  BP: Hypertension\na  Pericardium auscultation: Any Murmur, Carotid Bruit.\n\nInvestigation:\na  All Routines (CBC, RBS, S. Creatinine, Electrolytes, SGPT, Urine R/E)\na  Urgent CT Scan of Brain\na  ECG, CXR\na  Others as necessary for Etiology:\n   o  FBS, HbA1c\n   o  Fasting blood Lipid profile\n   o  Echocardiogram (if any murmur/ IHD)\n   o  Carotid color doppler (If Carotid bruit present)\n   o  S. FT3, FT4, TSH (If Atrial fibrillation is present)\n\nTreatment of Stroke:\n\nBefore CT Scan Brain:\n> If Patient is Conscious (Pt Can swallow without difficulty):\n  - Cap. Omeprazole 20 mg / Seclo 20mg\n    1+1+1\n  - Tab. Paracetamol 500mg (if headache)\n    2+2+2\n  - Tab. Pase / Epitra 0.5 mg(Clonazepam, esp. If anxious)\n    0+0+1\n\nPlus,\na  Anti Hypertensive: If BP is very high >220/120 mm hg (Inj. Labecard 4ml/20mg I/V slowly m\n   followed by tab Bizoran 5/20mg once daily) discussed later.\na  Anti Diabetic: If Uncontrolled Diabetes/ RBS is very high on admission. (Preferably Inj. Maxsul\n   S/C 8Hourly, Ensure Diabetic feeding, Frequent RBS check eg 8hrly.) discussed later\n\n> If Patient is Unconscious (Pt Can not swallow/ difficulty in swallowing): Rx as unconscious pt:\n  - NPO TFO\n  - NG feeding (Non diabetic pt -> Revit R Milk/ Diabetic pt-> RN Diabetes Milk)\n    200 ml 2hourly 10 times daily\n  - Inf. NS 1000ml\n    I/V @ 10 d/min daily\n  - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm / Ceftron 1 gm\n    1 vial I/V stat & once daily\n  - Inj. Omeprazole 40 mg/ Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V slowly stat & 12 hourly\n  - Inj Emistat/ ofran 8 mg\n    1 amp I/V stat & hourly\n\na  Anti Hypertensive: If BP is very high >220/120 mm hg (Inj. Labecard 4ml/20mg I/V slowly stat\n   followed by tab Bizoran 5/20mg once daily) discussed later.\na  Anti Diabetic: If Uncontrolled Diabetes/ RBS is very high on admission. (Inj Maxsulin S/C if NG\n   Feeding can be done, Otherwise I/V Insulin Infusion, RBS check 6-8hourly) discussed later.\na  If H/O Seizure/ Restless: Add -\n   - Inj Barbit 200mg\n     1 amp I/M stat and 12 hourly\n\na  If H/O Vomiting: Add -\n   - Inj Emistat 8mg\n     1 amp I/V stat and 8 hourly\n\na  Other Rx of Unconscious patient:\n   - Continuous catheterization\n   - SQ mycetin E/D 1-2 drops in each eye for 3-4 times daily / I. Guard S/L\n   - Nystat oral solution 2 ml per orally around tongue 3-4 times daily\n   - Changing posture 2 hourly\n\nAfter CT Scan Brain:\n> If Ischemic Stroke: Add followings with previous medications:\n  - Tab. Ecosprin/ Carva 75 mg\n    4 tab P/O stat then 0+1+0 (After meal)\n  - Tab. Anzitor 10mg/ Tiginor 10mg (Atorvastatin) / Xatono 10mg\n    0+0+1 (B/M)\n  - Tab. Vinpocetin/ Cerevas 5 mg/ cavinton 5mg\n    1+1+1   (for 2 Month)\n  - Tab. Phenytoin/ Diphedan 100mg (H/O or risk of seizure esp. large Infarction)\n    1+0+2\n\n> If Haemorrhagic Stroke: then:\n  - If Small Intracerebral haemorrhage: just conservative Rx, as given before CT scan\n  - If Large Intracerebral haemorrhage with midline shift: add -\n    - Inf Osmosol (20%) 500ml (Mannitol)\n      300 ml I/V running stat then\n      150 ml I/V running 8hourly for 3 days\n    - Inj. Barbit 200 mg\n      1 amp I/M 12hourly\n    - Inj. Anadol 100mg (With Inj. Emistat if not given before)\n      1 amp I/M stat and 8 hourly\n    - Urgent Neurosurgery call\n  - If ventricular extension of Haemorrhage: add -\n    - Tab. Nimodipin/ Nimocal 30 mg\n      2+2+2+2+2 (For 21 days)\n\n> If Sub-arachnoid Haemorrhage (SAH):\n  - Diet: Semisolid to Liquid, Plenty of fluid to maintain Hyperhydration (NPO - If repeated\n    vomiting)\n  - Inf. NS 1L + Inf 5% DNS 1L+ Inf H/S 1L\n    I/V @ 30 d/min daily\n  - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm / Ceftron 1 gm\n    1 vial I/V stat & once daily\n  - Inj. Omeprazole 40 mg/ Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V slowly stat & 12 hourly\n  - Inj. Napa 1 gm (Or Tab PCM 500mg 2+2+2 if conscious and less severe headache)\n    1 bottle I/V stat & 8 hourly\n  - Inj. Tramadol/ Anadol 100mg (Esp. If patient complains severe headache)\n    1 amp I/M stat and 8 hrly (NSAID cannot be given as it increases bleeding tendency)\n  - Inj. Ondansetron/ Emistat 8mg/ Ofran\n    1amp I/V stat and 8 hourly\n  - Inj. Barbit 200mg\n    1 amp I/M stat and 12hourly\n  - Tab. Nimodipin/ Nimocal 30mg\n    2+2+2+2+2+2\n  - Tab. clonazepam/ Pase/Epitra 0.5mg\n    0+0+2\n  - Syp. Lactulose/ Avolac/Osmolax (to avoid straining/constipation)\n    3 tsf TDS (after meal)\n\na  Antihypertensive: If BP> 180/120mm Hg -\n   - Tab. Camlosart / Bizoran (5/20mg)\n     1tab P/O stat & then 0+0+1\n\n"}, {"title": "Status Epilepticus Seizure Convulsion", "keywords": ["status", "epilepticus", "seizure", "convulsion"], "content": "\nStatus epilepticus/ Uncontrolled seizure or Convulsion\n\n- O2 inhalation\n  6-8L/min stat and SOS\n- Inj Sedil 10mg /1 ml + 9ml N/S or D/W\n  5 ml (5mg) I/V Slowing over 5mins stat.\n  If after 15 min there is no response, Repeat Inj Sedil as above. If no response then add:\n- Inj. Fosfen 150 mg\n  5 amp+ 500ml N/S I/V @ 120 d/min\n- Rx of underlying causes of status epilepticus: e.g. Hypoglycemia, Electrolytes imbalance,\n  stroke, Meningoencephalitis.\n- If no response with above all then call ICU\n\na  Restless due to any cause: Initially -\n   - Inj. Halopid 5 mg (or Inj Perol 5mg)\n     1 amp I/M stat&SOS\n   - Inj. Perkinil 5mg\n     1/2 amp I/M stat&SOS (along with Halopid)\na  If Still Restlessness is not controlled: Add -\n   - Inj. Opsonil 50 mg (with inj. Perkinil 1 amp I/M stat if not given within previous 12 hours)\n     1 amp I/M stat\n\nSedil (10mg + 9ml D/W)\n5 ml IV stat slowly / BD\n                                      (Cmistop)\n\n"}, {"title": "COPD Asthma", "keywords": ["copd", "asthma"], "content": "\nManagement of Acute exacerbation of COPD / Acute severe asthma\n\n- Complete bed rest\n- Diet: 01 (if severely distress then 04)\n- O2 Inhalation\n  2-4 L/min stat & SOS (in COPD)\n  4-6 L/min stat & SOS (in asthma)\n- Nebulization with Windel plus /Sulprex soulltion 0.5 ml + 1.5ml N/S\n  stat & 6 hrly (more frequently 2-4 hrly if pt is severely Dyspnic)\n- Inj. Moxaday 1.2 gm/ Clamox 1.2gm (If patient is stable Tab. Clamox 625mg 1+1+1)\n  1 Vail I/V stat & 8 hourly\n- Inj. Cotson 100 mg\n  2 vial I/V stat & 6hourly (If Pt is Diabetic then use 1 vial 6 hourly)\n- Tab. Doxiva / Flindof 200 mg\n  1+0+1\n- Cap. Omeprazole/ Seclo 20 mg\n  1+0+1 (B/M)\n- Tab. PCM 500/ Ace 500 (If fever)\n  1+1+1\n- Tab. Mucomist DT 600mg (If Thick Inspissated sputum)\n  1+0+1\n\na  In Acute Severe Asthma:\na  All Above except Mucomist\n   Plus\n   - Tab. Montene10mg / Odmon 10mg (Montelukast)\n     0+0+1 (Evening)\n   - Tab. Tofen/ Alarid 1 mg (Ketotifen)\n     0+0+1\n\na  In Life threatening Asthma not responding to above Rx: Add -\n   - Inj Nalepsin 100ml\n     50ml I/V @ 30d/min\n   - Call to ICU\n\na  At Discharge of COPD: (At least 24 hours to be stable on Inhalers/ routine medication without\n   need of nebulization)\n   - Tab. Moxaclav 625mg\n     1+1+1 (After meal) for 7 days\n   - Tab. Cortan 10mg/ Tab. Pred 10mg\n     4+0+0 (After meal) for 7 days\n   - Inhaler Sulprex/ Iprasol\n     2 puff inhale SOS (When respiratory distress or cough)\n   - Inhaler Ticamet/ Bexitrol F 250\n     2 puff Inhale 2 times daily - Continue (Gurgle after 2 puff use)\n   - Tab. Doxiva / Flindof 200 mg\n     1+0+1 - Continue\n   - Cap. Seclo 20 mg\n     1+0+1 (B/M) for 1 month\n   - Tab. Mucomist DT 600mg (If Thick Inspissated sputum)\n     1+0+1 for 1 month\n\na  At Discharge of Bronchial Asthma:\n   - Tab. Moxaclav 625mg\n     1+1+1 (After meal) for 7 days\n   - Tab. Cortan 10mg/ Tab. Pred 10mg\n     4+0+0 (After meal) for 7 days\n   - Inhaler Sultolin/ Ventolin\n     2 puff inhale SOS (When respiratory distress or cough)\n   - Inhaler Ticamet/ Bexitrol F 250\n     2 puff Inhale 2 times daily - Continue (Gurgle with water after 2 puff use)\n   - Tab. Montene 10mg\n     0+0+1 for 1 month (Longer if frequent attack)\n   - Tab. Tofen/ Alarid 1mg\n     0+0+1 for 1 month\n   - Cap. Seclo 20 mg\n     1+0+1 (B/M) for 1 month\n\n"}, {"title": "Pneumonia CAP", "keywords": ["pneumonia", "cap"], "content": "\na  In case both Asthma and COPD if frequent infective exacerbation: Consider vaccination.\n   - Inj. Influvax\n     1 amp I/M stat (And repeat annually)\n   - Inj. Pneumo - 23\n     1 amp I/M stat\n\nManagement of severe/complicated community acquired pneumonia (CAP)\n\nInvestigation:                        Rx on admission:\n- CBC with ESR                        - Diet: 01 (Normal)\n- CXR P/A View                       - O2 Inhalation\n- S. Creatinine                         4-6 L/min stat & continuous\n- Blood urea                         - Nebulization with Windel plus 0.5 ml + 1.5ml N/S\n- Sputum for C/S                       stat & 6 hourly\n- ECG                                - Inf. N/S 1L\n- S. Electrolytes                       I/V @ 10 drops/min daily\n- Other routine: RBS, SGPT,          - Inj. Moxaclav 1.2 gm\n  Urine R/E                            1  vial I/V stat & 8 hourly.\n                                      - Tab. Clarin 500mg/ Remac(Clarithromycin)\nDaily follow-up:                        1+0+1\n- Blood pressure                     - Tab. PCM 500mg\n- Pulse                                2+2+2 (A/M)\n- Respiratory rate                    - Cap. Omeprazole 20mg\n- Cyanosis                             1+0+1 (B/M)\n- GCS                                - Tab. Fenadin 120mg/Fexo(If Rhinorrhoea/cough)\n- Complaints of patient.                0+0+1\n\nCall to ICU may needed\n\na  If vomiting presents: Add -\n   - Inj. Emistat 8mg\n     1 amp I/V stat and TDS\n   - Make every drug injectable/ suppository.\n\nDischarge treatment of Severe / complicated pneumonia (CAP)\n\n- Tab. Moxaclav 625mg (after meal)\n  1+1+1 for 14 days\n- Tab. Remac / Clarin 500mg (Clarithromycin 500mg)\n  1+0+1 for 14 days\n- Tab. Ace/ Paracetamol 500mg\n  1+1+1 if fever persist\n- Cap. Nexum 20mg\n  1+0+1 (before meal) for 14 days\n\na  If cough/ respiratory distress present or associated with bronchial asthma:\n   - Tab. Montelukast/Montene 10 mg\n     0+0+1 - for 15 days.\n   - Inhaler Sultolin HFA/Sulbutamol\n     2  Puff inhale (Use when necessary.)\n\na  Advice:\n   - Follow-up with repeat CXR P/A view &CBC, ESR after 6 weeks\n\na  How to asses severity of pneumonia:\n   - CURB-65 score:\n     o  C= Confusion\n     o  U= Blood urea > 7 mmol/l\n     o  R= Resp. Rate > 30/min\n     o  B= Blood pressure, Systolic <90, Diastolic <60.\n     o  Age >65 years.\n     o  Score 1 for each point.\n   - Interpretation:\n     o  Score 0/1= Home treatment may given.\n     o  Score 2= Hospital supervised treatment needed.\n     o  Score 3/more = Severe CAP. (ICU support needed if score 4-5)\n   - Patient of pneumonia with complications should be admitted in hospital and should be\n     treated as severe pneumonia.\n\nTreatment of uncomplicated / mild to moderate community acquired pneumonia (CAP)\n\nInvestigation:                        Rx on admission:\n- CBC with ESR                        - Diet: 01 (Normal)\n- CXR P/A View                       - O2 Inhalation\n- S. Creatinine                         4-6 L/min stat & SOS\n- Blood urea                         - Nebulization with Windel plus 0.5 ml + 1.5ml N/S\n- Sputum for C/S                       stat & SOS\n- S. Electrolytes                     - Tab. Moxaclav 625mg\n- Other routine: RBS, SGPT,            1+1+1\n  Urine R/E                          - Tab. PCM 500mg\n                                        2+2+2 (A/M)\nDaily follow-up:                      - Cap. Omeprazole 20mg\n- Blood pressure                        1+0+1 (B/M)\n- Pulse                              - Tab. Fenadin 120mg/Fexo(If Rhinorrhoea/cough)\n- Respiratory rate                      0+0+1\n- Cyanosis\n- GCS\n- Complaints of patient.\n\nDischarge treatment of uncomplicated / mild to moderate CAP\n\n- Tab. Moxaclav 625mg (after meal)\n  1+1+1 for 14 days\n- Tab. Ace / Paracetamol 500mg\n  1+1+1 if fever persist\n- Cap. Nexum 20mg\n  1+0+1 (before meal) for 14 days\n\na  If cough/ respiratory distress present or associated with bronchial asthma:\n   - Tab. Montelukast/Montene 10 mg\n     0+0+1 - for 15 days.\n   - Inhaler Sultolin HFA/Sulbutamol\n     3  Puff inhale (Use when necessary.)\n\nAdvice:\n   - Follow-up with repeat CXR P/A view & CBC, ESR after 6 weeks\n\n"}, {"title": "Hospital Acquired Pneumonia", "keywords": ["hospital", "acquired", "pneumonia"], "content": "\nManagement of hospital acquired pneumonia\n\nInvestigation:                        Rx on admission:\n- CBC with ESR                        - Diet: 01 (Normal)\n- CXR P/A View                       - O2 Inhalation\n- S. Creatinine                         4-6 L/min stat & continuous\n- Blood urea                         - Nebulization with Windel plus 0.5 ml + 1.5ml N/S\n- Sputum for C/S                       stat & 6 hourly\n- ECG                                - Inf. N/S 1L\n- S. Electrolytes                       I/V @ 10 drops/min daily\n- Other routine: RBS, SGPT,          - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1g\n  Urine R/E                            1 vial I/V stat and BD\n                                      - Tab. PCM 500mg\nDaily follow-up:                        2+2+2 (A/M)\n- Blood pressure                     - Cap. Omeprazole 20mg\n- Pulse                                1+0+1 (B/M)\n- Respiratory rate                    - Tab. Fenadin 120mg/Fexo(If Rhinorrhoea/cough)\n- Cyanosis                             0+0+1\n- GCS\n- Complaints of patient.\n\na  If vomiting presents: Add -\n   - Inj. Emistat 8mg\n     1 amp I/V stat and TDS\n   - Make every drug injectable/ suppository.\n\n"}, {"title": "Aspiration Pneumonia", "keywords": ["aspiration", "pneumonia"], "content": "\nManagement of Aspiration pneumonia\n\nInvestigation:                        Rx on admission:\n- CBC with ESR                        - Diet: 01 (Normal)\n- CXR P/A View                       - O2 Inhalation\n- S. Creatinine                         4-6 L/min stat & continuous\n- Blood urea                         - Nebulization with Windel plus 0.5 ml + 1.5ml N/S\n- Sputum for C/S                       stat & 6 hourly\n- ECG                                - Inf. N/S 1L\n- S. Electrolytes                       I/V @ 10 drops/min daily\n- Other routine: RBS, SGPT,          - Inj. Moxaclav 1.2 gm\n  Urine R/E                            1 vial I/V stat & 8 hourly\n                                      - Inj. Metronidazole 100ml\nDaily follow-up:                        1 bottle I/V stat and 8 hourly\n- Blood pressure                     - Inj. Omeprazole 40mg\n- Pulse                                1 vial I/V stat and BD\n- Respiratory rate                    - Inj. Cotson 100mg\n- Cyanosis                             1 vial I/V stat and 6 hourly\n- GCS                                - Suppository Napa 500mg\n- Complaints of patient.               1 stick P/R stat and SOS\n                                      - Call to ICU (if not responding to treatment and severe\n                                        respiratory distress present)\n\na  If vomiting presents: Add -\n   - Inj. Emistat 8mg\n     1 amp I/V stat and TDS\n\n"}, {"title": "Heart Failure LVF", "keywords": ["heart", "failure", "lvf"], "content": "\nManagement of acute LVF/ Heart Failure without shock\n\nInvestigation:\n- ECG\n- CXR P/A View\n- S. Troponin I\n- Other routine: CBS with ESR, RBS, S. Creatinine, S. Electrolytes.\n- Later Echocardiogram when pt is stable\n- Also S. Pro BNP or BNP if available.\n\nDaily follow-up:\n- Blood pressure\n- Pulse\n- Respiratory rate\n- Cyanosis\n- GCS\n- Complaints of patient.\n\nRx on admission:\n- Diet - 01\n    - Fluid Restriction (Up to 1000ml/day)\n    - Salt Restriction\n- Complete Bed Rest\n- Propped up position\n- O2 inhalation\n  4-6 L/min Stat & SOS\n- Inj. Lasix/ Fusid 20 mg\n  2 amp I/V Stat & BD (8am, 4pm)\n- Inj. Morphine 15 mg\n  1 vial (mixed with 1 ml D/W) + 14 ml N/S then\n  3 ml (3mg) I/V slowing stat & SOS\n- Inj. Emistat / Ofran (Ondansetron) 8 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat and SOS (with Inj Morphine)\n- Anril Spray\n  2 puff sub lingually stat and SOS\n- Tab Nidocard RTD / Anril SR (Nitroglycerin) 2.6 mg\n  1+1+0\n- Tab Angilock 50 mg (25 mg if < 140/90 mmHg)\n  0+0+1\n\nIf underlying etiology is IHD then also add:\n- Tab. Ecosprin / Carva 75 mg\n  0+1+0 (A/M)\n- Tab. Clopid / Anclog (Clopidogrel) 75 mg\n  0+1+0 (A/M)\n- Tab. Atova/ Anzitor (Atorvastatin) 10 mg\n  0+0+1 (B/M)\n- Tab.Metacard MR / Angivent MR (Trimetazidine) 35mg\n  1+0+1\n- Cap. Omeprazole/ Seclo 20 mg\n  1+0+1 (Before Meal)\n\no If Acute Heart failure is settled: Add -\n    - Tab Carvista/ Durol (Carvedilol) 6.25 mg\n      1/2 +0+1/2 (Or Tab. Bisocor 2.5mg 1+0+0)\n\nAcute LVF or heart failure + Hypotension/ Cardiogenic Shock, BP < 90/60 mm\n\n- Diet -01\n    - Fluid restriction (Up to 1000ml/day)\n    - Salt restriction\n- Completed bed rest\n- Propped up position\n- O2 inhalation\n  4-6 L/min Stat & SOS\n- Inj.Dobutamin/ Dobutin 250mg\n  2 vial + 500ml N/S then I/V @ 32 ud/min & Titrate dose acc BP response\n- Inj. Lasix / Fusid 20 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat & BD (8am, 4 pm)\n\no If associated IHD: Also add-\n    - Tab. Ecosprin / Carva 75 mg\n      0+1+0 (A/M)\n    - Tab. Clopid / Anclog (Clopidogrel) 75 mg\n      0+1+0 (A/M)\n    - Tab. Atova/ Anzitor (Atorvastatin) 10 mg\n      0+0+1 (B/M)\n    - Tab. Metacard MR / Angivent MR (Trimetazidine) 35mg\n      1+0+1\n    - Cap. Omeprazole/ Seclo 20 mg\n      1+0+1 (Before Meal)\n\n"}, {"title": "Cardiogenic Shock Heart Failure Hypotension", "keywords": ["cardiogenic", "shock", "heart", "failure", "hypotension"], "content": "\nManagement of Stable Angina\n\n> Diagnosis:\n  o Moderate to severe Chest pain on exertion, No pain or Mild pain at rest.\n  o ST depression, T- wave Inversion.\n  o Troponin- I: Negative.\n\n> Treatment:\n- Diet: 01\n- Tab. Ecosprin / Carva 75 mg (Tab. Clopid 75mg 0+1+0 when Tab. Aspirin is contraindicated\n  e.g. Acute Asthma/COPD, Bleeding PUD)\n  0+1+0 (A/M)\n- Tab. Atova/ Anzitor (Atorvastatin) 10 mg\n  0+0+1 (B/M)\n- Tab Betaloc 25mg\n  1+0+1\n- Tab Nidocard RTD / Anril SR (Nitroglycerin) 2.6 mg\n  1+1+0 (1/2+ 1/2 + 0 if Systolic BP is < 110 and Hold if Systolic BP < 100mmHg)\n- Tab. Metacard MR / Angivent MR (Trimetazidine) 35mg\n  1+0+1\n- Cap. Omeprazole/ Seclo 20 mg\n  1+0+1 (Before Meal)\n\nTreatment of any associated Co-morbidity e.g: HTN, DM)\n\no For HTN:\n    - Tab Osartil / Angilock 50 mg (Or, Rameril 2.5mg 0+0+1)\n      0+0+1\n\nManagement of Unstable Angina & Acute Non- ST elevated MI\n\n> Diagnosis:\n  o Severe chest pain at rest.\n  o ST depression, T- wave Inversion.\n  o Troponin- I:\n      - Negative (Unstable Angina)\n      - Positive (Acute Non- ST elevated MI)\n  o Echocardiogram- Hypokinesia (Non- ST elevated MI)\n\n"}, {"title": "Angina", "keywords": ["angina"], "content": "\n> Treatment: Shift this patient to CCU Urgently.\n- Diet - 01\n- Complete Bed Rest\n- O2 inhalation\n  4-6 L/min stat and SOS\n- Inj. Clexane/ Clotinex 40(Enoxaparin) [More dose may be needed according to weight]\n  1 PFS S/C stat & BD [For usually upto 7 days]\n- Tab. Ecosprin / Carva 75 mg\n  4 Tab P/O stat then\n  0+1+0 (A/M)\n- Tab. Clopid / Anclog (Clopidogrel) 75 mg\n  4 Tab P/O stat then\n  0+1+0 (A/M)\n- Tab. Atova/ Anzitor (Atorvastatin) 10 mg\n  0+0+1 (B/M)\n- Anril Spray/ GTN spray\n  2 puff sub lingually stat and SOS\n- Tab. Nidocard RTD /Anril SR (Nitroglycerin) 2.6 mg\n  1+1+0\n- Tab. Betaloc 25mg\n  1+0+1\n- Tab. Angilock 50mg/ Cardon\n  0+0+1 (Use 0+0+1/2 if BP < 140/90 mmHg)\n- Tab.Metacard MR / Angivent MR ( Trimetazidine) 35mg\n  1+0+1\n- Cap Omeprazole/ Seclo 20 mg\n  1+0+1 (Before Meal)\n\nIn Case of Acute MI / Unstable angina for severe pain:\n- Inj. Morphine 15 mg       (Alternative-Inj Pethidine 1/2 amp IV slowly stat & sos)\n  1 vial (mixed with 1 ml D/W) + 14 ml N/S then 3 ml (3mg) I/V slowly stat & SOS\n- Inj. Emistat / Ofran ( Ondansetron) 8 mg\n  1 vial I/V stat & SOS with Morphine [or Inj. Vergon]\n\n"}, {"title": "Unstable Angina NSTEMI", "keywords": ["unstable", "angina", "nstemi"], "content": "\nManagement of ST elevated MI\n\n> If patient comes within 12 hours of onset of chest pain:\n    - Management of Non-ST elevated MI (except S/C Inj. Enoxaparin)\n      Plus,\n    - Inj. STK 1.5 million (Streptokinase)\n      1 amp. Mixed with 100ml N/S then I/V @ 100 microdrops / Mins\n    - If primary coronary intervention (PCI) is available then PCI is preferred to\n      Streptokinase.\n\no Relative contraindications of Streptokinase:\n    - Previous Intracerebral haemorrhage or sub-arachnoid haemorrhage\n    - Active internal bleedin, Bleeding PUD\n    - Uncontrolled HTN (Systolic BP > 180mmHg)\n    - Recent surgery or trauma especially Head trauma (Within one month)\n    - Pregnancy\n\n> If patient comes after 12 hours of onset of chest pain:\n    - Same management as Non-ST elevated MI\n\n"}, {"title": "STEMI MI", "keywords": ["stemi", "mi"], "content": "\nShock Management (BP< 90/60 mm Hg with Feeble or absent pulse)\n\n> If BP < 90/60mmHg then Check following:\n  o History:\n    - Any H/O Vomiting/ Diarrhea/ Bleeding (Hypovolemic)\n    - H/O Chest pain, Respiratory Distress (Cardiogenic)\n    - H/O Fever, RTI/ UTI (Septic)\n  o Examination:\n    - Pulse- Feeble, tachycardia or Absent\n    - Peripheral Limbs- Cold, Sweating (Other than Septic Shock)\n    - Warm periphery (May be Septic shock)\n    - Chest- Lung Bases for any Basal Crepitation (Cardiogenic with HF)\n\nHYPOVOLEMIC SHOCK\n\n> Diagnosis:\n  o BP<90/60 mm, Pulse: Feeble.\n  o Dehydration:Sunk on eye, drytongue\n  o H/OAWD/ Vomiting/Blood loss.\n\n> Treatment:\n- Diet-01\n- Inf. Normal Saline 1000ml\n  I/V @ running stat then\n- Inf N/S (1L) + Inf 5% DNS (1L) + Inf Hartsol (1L)\n  I/V @ 60 d/min\n- Rx of underlying cause (AWD, Vomiting, Blood loss)\n\nIf BP is not increased after adequate fluid resuscitation correcting hypovolumia then add:\n- Inj. Noradrenaline / Levofed /Hyponor\n  2amp + Inf N/S (1L) then I/V @ 30 d/min\n- Check BP at 30 min interval & titrate dose accordingly\n\n"}, {"title": "Shock Management", "keywords": ["shock", "management"], "content": "\nCARDIOGENIC SHOCK\n\n> Diagnosis:\n  o BP < 90/60 mm, Pulse: Feeble\n  o H/O Chest Pain and breathlessness\n  o ECG - AMI\n  o S. Troponin I - Positive\n\n> Treatment:\n- Inf. Normal Saline 500ml (Maximum 1000ml) [if no acute LVF]\n  I/V @ running stat\n\nIf BP is not increased or shock with LVF then:\n- Inj.Dobutamin/ Dobutin 250mg (Along with I/V fluid infusion by another cannula)\n  2 vial + 500ml N/S then I/V @ 32 ud/min\n- Check BP at 30 min interval & titrate dose accordingly\n- Rx of underlying cause (Rx of AMI)\n- Transfer the patient to CCU\n\nSEPTIC SHOCK\n\n> Diagnosis:\n  o BP < 90/60 mm, Pulse: Feeble\n  o Fever, Warm periphery\n\n> Investigations:\n  o Send blood for C/S, CBC, CRP, S. Creatinine, S. Procalcitonin (If available)\n  o Urine R/M/E & C/S, Chest X-ray P/A view, ECG\n\n> Treatment:\n- Inf. Normal Saline 1000ml (if no acute LVF)\n  500ml I/V running Then @ 30d/min\n- Inj. Noradrenaline / Levofed/Hyponor\n  2amp + Inf N/S (1L) then I/V @ 30 d/min\n- Inj. Meropen / Spechac 1g (Meropenem) (500mg in renal impairment)\n  1vial I/V stat & 8 hourly\n- Inj. Omeprazole 40mg\n  1vial I/V stat and BD\n- Check BP at 30 min interval & titrate the rate of Noradrenaline infusion accordingly\n- Call to ICU if BP is not rising despite Noradrenaline infusion.\n\nANAPHYLACTIC SHOCK\n\n> Diagnosis:\n  o BP < 90/60 mm, Pulse: Feeble.\n  o Respiratory distress, Urticaria / Skin rash with itching following exposure of allergens, food,\n    Chemical, Bee sting.\n\n> Treatment:\n- O2 inhalation\n  8-10 L/min stat and continue\n- Nebulization with Windel plus 0.5 ml + 1.5ml N/S\n  stat & SOS\n- Inf. Normal Saline 1000ml\n  I/V @ running stat\n- Inj. Adrinor / Adrin 1mg (Adrenalin)\n  1/2 amp I/M stat (Can be repeated at 10 minutes interval if required)\n- Inj. Cotson 100mg\n  2 vial I/V stat and then 1 vial I/V 8 hourly\n- Inj. Avil 2ml\n  1 amp I/M stat and once daily\n- Tab. Famostack 40mg / Famotid 40mg\n  1+0+1\n\nManagement of Hypertension without Comorbidity or complication\n\nAge < 55 years\n- Tab. Angilock 50mg/ Osartil / Cardon (Or Tab Olmecar 20/Abetis 20/Olmesan 20)\n  0+0+1 (dose can be increased up to 100mg if needed) (Angiotensin Receptor Blocker - ARB)\n  Or,\n- Tab. Ramoril / Ripril 2.5 mg (ACE inhibitor)\n  0+0+1 (dose can be upto 5-10mg if needed)\n\nAge > 55 years\n- Tab Amdocal/ Camlodin 5 mg (Or Tab Cilma/Cildip10) (Calcium Channel Blocker - CCB)\n  1+0+0 (Dose Can be up to 10mg if needed)\n\n> If BP is still not controlled after 1-2 weeks of therapy: Then go for A+C\n    - Tab. Camlosart / Bizoran (5/20 mg)(Olmesartan + Amlodipine)\n      0+0+1\n\n> If still not improved after 1-2 week: Check the compliance of medication. If patient is compliant,\n  then increase the dose of above medication Increase the dose of A/C\n    - Tab. Camlosart / Bizoran (5/40 mg)\n      0+0+1\n\n  If still not controlled then:\n    - Tab. Camlosart / Bizoran (5/40 mg)\n      0+0+1\n      plus\n    - Tab. Amdocal / Camlodin 5 mg\n      1+0+0\n\no If BP is still not controlled after 1-2 weeks: Then go for A+C+D\n    - Previous medications\n      Plus,\n    - Tab. Natrilix SR 1.5mg/ Repres SR/Hypen SR (Indapamide, a thiazide like duretics)\n      1+0+0\n\n"}, {"title": "Hypertension", "keywords": ["hypertension"], "content": "\nManagement of Hypertension with comorbidity or complication\n\nHTN+IHD\n- Tab. Bisocor /Bispro (Bisoprolol) 2.5mg\n  0+0+1 (Can be increased dose to 5mg daily or twice daily if needed)\n  Or,\n- Tab. Tenoloc 50mg\n  0+0+1\n\nHTN+HEARTFAILURE/ LV DYSFUNCTION/POST-MI STATE\n- Tab. Ramoril / Ripril 2.5 mg\n  0+0+1 (Can be increased upto 10mg if needed)\n  Or\n- Tab. Angilock 50mg/ Osartil/ Cardon (Tab Olmecar 20, Abetis 20/Olmesan20)\n  0+0+1 (If ACE inhibitor e.g. Ripril/ Ramoril is intolerable due to coughing/ Angioedema)\n  Can be increased up to 100mg if needed.\n\nHTN + CKD\n- Tab. Amdocal/ Camlodin 5mg (Or Tab Cilma/Cildip10)\n  1+0+0 (Can be up to 10 mg daily if needed)\n  If not controlled, then add:\n    - Tab. Alphapress / Prazolock 1 mg\n      1+1+1 (Dose can be upto 12 mg daily e.g. Alphapress 2mg 2+2+2)\n\nHTN+DIABETES\n- Tab. Ramoril / Ripril 2.5 mg (In Type 1 DM)\n  0+0+1 (Can be increased upto 10mg if needed)\n- Tab. Angilock 50mg/ Osartil/ Cardon(Tab Olmecar 20/Abetis 20/Olmesan20) (In\n  0+0+1                                Type 2 DM)\n\nSevere Hypertension (BP> 180/120mmHg)\n\nHYPERTENSIVE URGENCY\n\n> Severe hypertensive (BP > 180/120mmHg) & No Signs of acute end organ damage. No Signs of -\n    - Papilledema\n    - Encephalopathy\n    - Acute Stroke\n    - Acute MI\n    - Acute Renal Failure\n\n> Treatment: Oral Antihypertensive:\n    - Tab. Bizoran / Camlosart 5/40mg\n      1 tab P/O stat then\n      0+0+1\n    - Tab. Napa 500mg / Ace\n      2+2+2 - if there is headache\n    - Tab. Pase / Epitra ( Clonazepam) 0.5mg\n      0+0+1\n\nHYPERTENSIVE EMERGENCIES\n\n> Severe hypertensive (BP>180/120mmHg) & Signs of acute end organ damage. Presence of any signs\n  of -\n    - Papilledema\n    - Encephalopathy\n    - Acute Stroke\n    - Acute MI\n    - Acute Renal Failure\n\n> Investigations:\n    - Urgent ECG, Troponin I (if chest pain)\n    - CT scan brain (if any significant neurological sign)\n    - S. Creatinine, Urine R/E\n\n> Treatment: Usually I/V antihypertensive is required for immediate control of BP. Then maintain\n  with oral antihypertensive\n\n> Rx of different hypertensive emergencies are given below:\n\nHYPERTENSIVE ENCEPHALOPATHY\n\n> Clinical features:\n  Severe HTN (BP > 180/120 mmHg) + Signs of encephalopathy(altered consciousness,\n  headache, vomiting, papilledema, bilateral plantar extension)\n  No focal s/s of stroke e.g. hemiparesis\n  CT scan Brain- diffuse cerebral edema\n\n> Treatment:\n- Inj. Labecard 5mg/Amp\n  4ml (20mg) I/V slowly stat & SOS\n  Contraindications of labecard: Acute LVF, Acute COPD/ Acute Asthma\n- Tab. Camlosart 5/40 mg/ Bizoran\n  0+0+1\n  Plus,\n- Other treatment of unconscious stat.\n\nSEVERE HYPERTENSION WITH ACUTE STROKE\n\n> Clinical features:\n  BP > 180/120 mmHg + Signs of acute stroke (hemiparesis, unilateral plantar extension,\n  aphasia, cranial nerve lesion/intracranial haemorrhage.\n  CT scan brain - (+) Infarction/Intracerebral haemorrhage.\n\n> Treatment:\n- Give antihypertensive (Inj Labecard + Tab Bizoran / Camlosart 5/40 as above) only if\n    - Any type of acute stroke with BP > 220/120mmHg\n    - Hemorrhagic stroke with features of raised ICT (Severe headache, vomiting,\n      papilledema) or SAH\n- In other cases do not add antihypertensive (may be added after 1 week/ at discharge)\n\n"}, {"title": "Severe Hypertension Emergency", "keywords": ["severe", "hypertension", "emergency"], "content": "\nSEVERE HYPERTENSION WITH ACUTE LVF/ ACUTE MI (BP>180/120 mmHg)\n\n> Treatment:\n- Ideally I/V GTN Infusion starting with 5-10 mg/min. This needs cardiac monitoring so can't\n  be given on medicine ward, ideally given in the CCU.\n\n  In medicine ward:\n- Tab. Angilock 50mg/ Doartil 50 mg\n  0+0+2\n- Inj. Lasix 20mg / Fusid 20 mg\n  2 amp I/V stat & BD (8am & 4 pm)\n- Anril spray/ Nidocard spray\n  2 puff S/L Stat & SOS\n  Plus,\n- Others standard treatment of acute LVF/AMI.\n\nManagement of diabetes Mellitus\n\n> Any Acute condition with poorly controlled diabetes (RBS > 15 mmol/L):(But not considering\n  DKA or HONK)\n  e.g. Acute stroke, Acute MI, Acute HF, Renal Failure, Sepsis, Acute Pancreatitis, Severe Infection,\n  severe pneumonia, Pyelonephritis, Leg ulcer, Gangrine.\n\n  If patient is not in Insulin treatment, than start:\n    - Inj. Maxsulin/ Ansulin S-100, U-100\n      4+4+4 (+2) - S/C 15-30 min B/M (Higher doses may be needed depending on higher\n      level of blood sugar e.g 6+6+4 when RBS-20)\n    - If the patient is getting any prescribed insulin before, than continue it & talk to you senior for\n      any changes.\n\n> Acute abdomen or any other condition keeping patient NPO with poorly controlled Diabetes\n  o Talk to your senior for the management of diabetes.\n  o May be Glucose Insulin infusion needed. Which can be given by 2 ways:\n\n  i) Half neutralizing dose: (when risk of hypoglycemia is more)\n    - Inf 5% DNS 1000ml + Inj. Maxsulin /Ansulin 10 units\n      I/V @ 20 d/min\n\n  ii) Full neutralizing dose: (when less risk of hypoglycemia)\n    - Inf 5% DNS 1000ml + Inj. Maxsulin /Ansulin 20 unites\n      I/V @ 20 d/min\n\n> In case of patients newly diagnosed as Diabetes, start treatment with insulin in the following\n  conditions:\n  o All type 1 DM (Young, Cachectic Patients)\n  o Type 2 DM with: HbA1C> 10, RBS >17 mmol/L, Catabolic State(Polyuria, Polydipsia, wt\n    loss)\n  o Acute complications (DKA, HONK, Renal failure, AMI, Stroke, Sepsis)\n  o Gestational DM\n  o Start Insulin as below (Except DKA/ HONK for which specific guideline see later):\n    - Inj. Maxsulin/ Ansulin (S-100, U-100)\n      4+4+4 (+2) - S/C 15-30 min B/M (Higher doses may be needed depending on higher level of\n      blood sugar e.g. 6+6+4 when RBS - 20)\n\n"}, {"title": "Diabetes Mellitus", "keywords": ["diabetes", "mellitus"], "content": "\n> For Poorly Controlled diabetes Follow-up Blood sugar daily as:\n  o Check Fasting blood sugar (FBS) &2 hr ABF Daily & Maintain diabetic chart.\n\nIf target blood sugar is still not achieved by initial dose than the dose of insulin by 2 units twice\nweekly (after 2 days). e.g: If Pt is getting:\n- Inj. Maxsulin / Ansulin (S-100, U-100)\n  4+4+4 (+2) S/C 15-30 min B/M\n\nTarget is not achieved after 2 days then:\n- Inj. Maxsulin / Ansulin (S-100, U-100)\n  6+6+4 (+2) S/C 15-30 min B/M\n\n> For very Fluctuating diabetes (Alternating Hyper & Hypoglycemia episodes):\n  o Check FBS, 2hrs ABF, BL, BD daily(BL-before Lunch, BD-Before Dinner)\n  o Maintain diabetic chart:\n    - In this case talk to senior for management of blood sugar.\n    - Sliding scale maybe followed for safer control of blood sugar where insulin dose is\n      given according to pre-meal blood sugar level as follows.\n\nBlood Sugar level          | Insulin dose to be given (Subcutaneously)\n< 6 mmol/L                | No insulin at that time\n6-10 mmol/L               | 4 units S/C\n10 -12 mmol/L             | 6 units S/C\n12-15 mmol/L              | 8 units S/C\n>15 mmol/L                | 10 units S/C (or more if very high sugar)\n\n> Newly diagnosed Diabetes without complication or acute conditions:\n  o Tab. Comet 500 mg (Metformin)\n    1/2 +0+1/2 (After meal) - for 7 days\n    then 1+0+1 (after meal). If still not controlled after 2 weeks\n    then 1+1+1 (After meal) [may be increased dose upto total 2000mg daily]\n\n  Or,\n  o Tab. Linatab 5mg/ Linita ( Linagliptin) 5 mg\n    0+1+0 (before meal)\n\nContraindications of Metformin: Renal failure, heart failure, sepsis, hepatic failure (can cause lactic\nacidosis in these conditions)\n\n> If Metformin(Comet) is contraindicated then consider following ( or If Metformin is\n  ineffective upto 2000mg then add):\n  o Tab. Linatab 5mg/ Linita ( Linagliptin) 5 mg\n    0+1+0 (before meal)\n  o Tab. Comprid 80mg/ Dimerol (Gliclazide)\n    1+0+0 ( 30 min Before meal)\n    [ Alternative - Tab. Secrin 2mg (Glimepiride), 1+0+0 (30 min Before meal)]\n\nDIABETIC KETOACIDOSIS / SEVERELY UNCONTROLLED DM\n\n> Clinical features of diabetic ketoacidosis:\n  o Patient is unwell, restless and altered consciousness may present.\n  o Fever, respiratory distress, Vomiting, Abdominal pain\n  o Features pneumonia/ UTI/Sepsis/AMI/Stroke\n  o Features of severe or moderate dehydration, ↑pulse, ↓BP\n  o Maybe H/O DM. On inadequate/irregular antidiabetic treatment\n\nInvestigations:\n  o Do Urgent beside RBS (Usually high > 15 mmol/L)\n  o Then do Urgent -\n    - S electrolytes including HCO3 (HCO3< 18 in Diabetic ketoacidosis )\n    - Urine for keton bodies (+ve)\n    - Also Consider - CBS, S Uria, S. Creatinine, SGPT, Urine R/E\n    - ECG, Tropnin -I(If H/O chest pain/ECG change/sweating/heart failure)\n  o After stabilizing patient -\n    - CXR P/A view (if suspect pneumonia)\n    - CT Scan of Brain (If stroke is excepted)\n  o Repeat S. Electrolytes & Urine for keton body 12 hourly (at least once daily)\n\nTreatment of diabetic ketoacidosis\n\no NPO TFO\no O2 Inhalation (If respiratory distress)        o Be careful in heart failure Renal\n  4-6L/min stat &sos                               Failure/ Elderly pts, check for any\no Inf. Normal Saline 4L                             signs of fluid overload eg lung\n  1L I/V @ Running (Over 1hr)                       crep (+) at bases, leg edema (+).\n  then, 1L I/V @ 120 d/min                          If present then less I/V fluid to be\n  then, 1L I/V @ 60 d/min                           given slowly.\n  then, Continue I/V fluid @ 30 d/min acc to dehydration level,\n  (Add- Inf. 5% DA (1L) @ 10 d/min when RBS <10mmol/L (Along with Inf. NS).\no Inj Maxsulin R/ Ansulin R (S-100, U-100)\n  24 units mixed in 100 ml N/S\n  I/V @ 24 ud/min until RBS < 15 mmol/L\n  then, 12 ud/min until RBS < 10 mmol/L\n  then, 6 ud/min until RBS < 6 mmol/L\n  (When, RBS < 6 mmol/L - stop I/V Infusion & talk to seinor for starting S/C Insulin\no Inj Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\no Continuous catheterization\no Maintain Diabetic Chart\n\n> Treat the precipitating condition (If any, like AMI, stroke, pneumonia/UTI/Sepsis).\n> Correct any associated electrolyte imbalance especially hypokalemia.\n> When RBS < 10 mmol/L then add\n> If I/V Insulin Infusion can not be given then give I/M as-\n    - Inj Ansulin R / Maxsulin R (S-100, U-100)\n      10 Units I/M Stat & 6 Hourly\n\n"}, {"title": "DKA Diabetic Ketoacidosis", "keywords": ["dka", "diabetic", "ketoacidosis"], "content": "\nHHS (HYPERGLYCAEMIC HYPEROSMOLAR SYNDROME) / HONK\n\n> Clinical features of HHS:\n  o Patient usually comes with altered\n    consciousness/ coma/ confusion.\n  o Severe dehydration (more marked than DKA).\n  o Hypotension/ Shock (usually hypovolemic).\n  o History is usually longer than DKA (eg unwell\n    for 7 days).\n  o RBS- is usually very high (> 30 mmol/L)\n  o S.HCO3 is usually > 18mmol/L, Urine for keton\n    body - Usually absent\n  o S. Osmolality > 320 mosm\n\n  S. Osmolality = 2 Na+ glucose (mmol/L)+ Urea (mmol/L)\n  Convert urea from mg/dl to mmol/L as below:\n  Urea (mmol/L) = Urea(Mg / dl)\n                        6\n\nInvestigations:\n  o Do Urgent beside RBS (Usually high >30 mmol/L)\n  o Then do Urgent -\n    - S electrolytes including HCO3 (HCO3> 18 in Diabetic ketoacidosis )\n    - Urine for keton bodies (- ve)\n    - Also Consider - CBS, S Uria, S. Creatinine, SGPT, Urine R/E\n    - ECG, Tropnin -I (If H/O chest pain/ECG change/sweating/heart failure)\n  o After stabilizing patient -\n    - CXR P/A view (if suspect pneumonia)\n    - CT Scan of Brain (If stroke is excepted)\n  o Repeat S. Electrolytes, S. Creatinine 12 hourly (at least once daily)\n\nTreatment of HHS\n\no NPO TFO                                        o Be careful in heart failure Renal\no O2 Inhalation (If respiratory distress)           Failure/ Elderly pts, check for any signs\n  4-6L/min stat & sos                               of fluid overload eg lung crep (+) at\no Inf. Normal Saline 4 L                             bases, leg edema (+). If present then\n  1L I/V @ Running                                   less I/V fluid to be given slowly.\n  1L I/V @ 120 d/min                              o If there are signs of dehydration after\n  1L I/V @ 60 d/min                                 4L N/S then more fluid may be\n                                                     necessary.\n  Continue I/V fluid @ 30 d/min acc to dehydration level,\no Inj Maxsulin R/ Ansulin R (S-100, U-100)\n  12 units mixed in 100 ml N/S (half strength of DKA)\n  I/V @ 24 ud/min until RBS < 15 mmol/L\n  then, 12 ud/min until RBS < 10 mmol/L\n  then, 6 ud/min until RBS < 6 mmol/L. Then titrate the dose of insulin according to blood sugar\no Inj Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\no Inj Clotinex/ Clexane ( Enoxaparine) 40 IU For prophylaxis of thrombo-embolis\n  1PFS S/C stat & one daily (If no contraindication e.g. bleeding major trauma/head injury)\no Continuous catheterization\no Check blood sugar 2 hourly\no Treatment of precipitating cause e.g. AMI /Spsis (If any)\n\nMANAGEMENT OF HYPOGLYCAEMIA (RBS < 3.9MMOL/L)\n\n> If patient is conscious and can swallow- Give Glucose drinks/ Sugar mixed water/ Fruit juice/ Sweet.\n> If patient is unconscious or can not swallow then:-\n    - Inf 5% DA (1L)/5% DNS 1000ml (or any glucose saline available in Ward)\n      200 ml I/V running stat then, I/V @ 15 d/min\n    - Inj. Nutridex 25% 100ml\n      I/V @ running stat\n\nHold all antidiabetic medications (Insulin/ Oral Antidiabetic drugs) which can be started later after\ncorrection of hypoglycemia in reduced dose (Talk to senior for adjustment usually 25% dose reduction\n\n"}, {"title": "HHS HONK Hyperosmolar", "keywords": ["hhs", "honk", "hyperosmolar"], "content": "\nAcute Abdomen (Severe Abdominal pain + Vomiting)\n\nInvestigations:\n  o S. lipase\n  o USG of Whole Abdomen\n  o X-ray abdomen A/P view in erect posture including both dome of diaphragm\n  o ECG (In case of epigastric pain)\n  o Other routine tests including S. Creatinine, S. electrolytes, SGPT, Urine R/M/E\n\n> Treatment:\n  o NPO TFO\n  o Inf. Normal Saline 1L+Inf. Hartsol 1L+ Inf. 5% DNS 1L (exclude DM)\n    I/V @ 30 d/min Daily\n  o Inj Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  o Inj Metronidazole /Amodis 100ml(Hold in severe vomiting & can be added after controlling vomiting)\n    1 bag I/V Stat & 8 hourly\n  o Inj Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  o Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n    1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\n  o Inj Anadol 100mg\n    1 amp I/M Stat & 12 hourly\n  o Inj Algin / Norvis 5 mg\n    1amp. I/V stat & 8 hourly\n\nIf pancreatitis/ Cholecystitis / Appendicitis is suspected then also add:\n  o Inj Rolac/ Torax 30 mg\n    1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\n\n> Severe pain not responding to above all medications then add:\n  o Inj Nalbun 2/ Radirf 2 (Nalbuphine)\n    1 amp I/M stat and sos\n\n"}, {"title": "Hypoglycaemia", "keywords": ["hypoglycaemia"], "content": "\nManagement of Acute Gastroenteritis\n\nAt first, Check for:\no Pulse, BP\no Periphery of the Limbs - Cold, Sweaty.\no Signs of Dehydration (Eye ball sunken, Dry Tongue, Decreased Skin Turgor)\no Urine Output\n\nMILD TO MODERATE ACUTE GASTRO-ENTERITIS\n\n> Clinical features:\n  o No dehydration\n  o Normal Pulse, BP\n\n> Treatment:\n  o Diet - 01:\n    - Plenty of Fluid Intake\n  o Orsaline-N Mixed with 500ml water\n    after each motion\n  o Tab. Ciprofloxacin 500mg/ Ciprocin\n    1+0+1..............5-7 days (After meal)\n  o Tab. Metronidazole 400/ Amodia (Hold in severe vomiting & can be added after controlling vomiting)\n    1+1+1..............5 days\n  o Tab Emistat 8mg/ Ofran(If H/O Vomiting)\n    1+1+1(Before meal)\n  o Tab. Sevipep 40mg / Famotid 40mg\n    1+0+1 (Before meal)\n\n"}, {"title": "Acute Abdomen", "keywords": ["acute", "abdomen"], "content": "\nMODERATE TO SEVERE ACUTE GASTRO-ENTERITIS (NOT IN SHOCK)\n\n> Clinical features:\n  o Severe Acute Watery Diarrhoea (AWD), Vomiting, Abdominal Pain.\n  o Dehydrated/ Hypotension / Tachycardia/ Reduced Urine Output\n\n> Treatment:\n  o Diet: Semisolid to liquid [NPO if Severe Vomiting/ Unconscious or Confused Pt]\n    - Plenty of Fluid Intake\n  o Orsaline-N\n    Mixed with 500ml water after each motion\n  o Inf. 5% DNS 1L+ Inf. Cholera Saline 1L\n    I/V @ 30 d/min daily\n    [If Patient has Reduced Urine output or features of AKI/ CKD then Don't Use Cholera Saline,\n    Hartsol as these can cause Hyperkalemia. In this case, use Normal saline]\n  o Inj. Ciprofloxacin 100ml/ 200mg\n    1 Bag I/V Stat & 12 Hourly\n  o Inj Metronidazole /Amodis 100ml(Hold in severe vomiting & can be added after controlling vomiting)\n    1 bag I/V stat & 8 hourly\n  o Inj Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  o Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n    1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\n\n> In AKI / Unconscious or confused patients:\n  o Continuous Catheterization\n  o Maintain I/O Chart\n\nSEVERE ACUTE GASTRO-ENTERITIS (IN SHOCK)\n\n> Clinical features:\n  o If Patient is in Shock (BP<90/60mmHg & Feeble or Absent Pulse, Cold Periphery)\n\n"}, {"title": "Gastroenteritis Diarrhea", "keywords": ["gastroenteritis", "diarrhea"], "content": "\n> Treatment:\nAt first resuscitate the patient by rapid bolus of I/V Fluid as below:\n  o Inf N/S 1000ml\n    I/V Running Stat over 15-30min\n\nIf No Response (still in shock) after Bolus fluid of 1000ml then:\n  o Inj Dopamin 200mg\n    2amp. mixed in 500ml N/S\n    I/V @ 32ud/min\n    Plus,\n  o Continue I/V fluid until correction of Hypovolumia/ Dehydration\n  o Continuous Catheterization\n  o Maintain Hourly Intake/Output Chart\n  o Other Medications of Severe Gastro-enteritis without shock (See above)\n  o Check Pulse, BP 1/2 hourly initially & Titrate Dopamin and Fluid dose accordingly consulting\n    with seniors.\n\nManagement of Acute Live failure\n\nHistory and Clinical features:\n  o Fever, Jaundice, Right upper abdominal pain, Vomiting: Acute viral Hepatitis ( Very High Rise of\n    SGPT usually >1000)\n  o High grade fever, Deep jaundice, Reduced urinary output: may be Leptospirosis (High Bilirubin,\n    mildly raised SGPT, raised S. Creatinine)\n  o Take any History of Taking Hepatotoxic drugs e.g. Paracetamol/ Herbal medication/ Anti-\n    TB/Antifungal/ NSAID.\n\nInvestigations:\n  o All patients: Routines investigations + SGPT, S. ALP, S. Bilirubin, Prothombin Time, S. Albumin, USG\n    W/A.\n  o If no cause is evident in history, then also do-\n    - Anti HAV IgM\n    - Anti HEV\n    - HBsAg,\n  o MAT for Leptospirosis (If Leptospirosis is suspected)\n\nTreatment on admission of Acute Liver Failure:\n  o Diet : Semisolid to Liquid; High Carbohydrat [If Unconscious: NG Feeding, If Severe Vomiting:\n    NPO TFO]\n  o Inf. 5%DA 1000ml\n    I/V @ 20 d/min - daily\n  o Inj. Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  o Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  o Inj. Konakion 10 mg\n    1 amp I/V slowly stat &once daily for 5days\n  o Tab. Rifagut 550 mg\n    1+1+1\n  o Tab. Motigut 10mg / Omidon 10mg\n    1+1+1 (B/M)\n  o Syp. Avolac/ Osmolax\n    4-5 TSF TDS\n  o Syp. Lola / Hepagurd\n    1 sachet mixed with 1 glass water TDS\n  o Fleet Enema/ Enema simplex\n    1 bottle P/R stat (If severe constipation not responding with above treatment)\n\nNo paracetamol, No NSAID, No Sedative, OPOIDS, Antidepressant, No Diuretics, No Anti-TB,\nNo Anti- Fungal\n\n> If signs of Cerebral Oedema (Headache, Vomiting, Confusion):\n  o Inj Osmosol 20%\n    300ml I/V running stat\n\n> If deep jaundice and itching present:\n  o Tab. Ursocol 300mg\n    1+0+1\n\n> Treatment of any precipitating/underlying cause:\n  Leptospirosis:\n  o Cap. Doxicap 100mg\n    1+0+1\n\n"}, {"title": "Acute Liver Failure", "keywords": ["acute", "liver", "failure"], "content": "\nParacetamol poisoning:\n  o Alistin 600mg / N-Acetylcysteine\n    14 tablet stat followed by\n    7 tablet 4 hourly for total 17 doses.\n\nManagement of CLD\n\n  o Diet: 01\n    - High Carbohydrate\n    - Fluid and Salt Restriction (If Severe Ascitis)\n  o Inj. Ceftriaxone 1g (If severe infection or Febrile/ Confusion/ Complicated)\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 Hourly\n  o Tab. Fusid plus (20/50)/Avoid Diuretics if there is Hepatic encephalopathy or Hypotension)\n    1+1+0\n  o Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n    1+0+1 (B/M)\n  o Tab. Domperidone 10mg/ Motigut 10mg / Omidon 10mg\n    1+1+1 (B/M)\n  o Syp. Avolac/ Osmolax\n    3 TSF TDS\n  o Tab. Indever 40mg(If there is any Oesophageal varices)\n    1+0+1\n\n  o No paracetamol, No NSAID, No Sedative, OPOIDs, Antidepressant, No Diuretics, No Anti-TB, No Anti-\n    Fungal.\n  o Fluid & Electrolyte Correction if any.\n\n> If severe ascites:\n    - Inj. Lasix\n      2amp I/V stat & bd: 8am, 4pm\n\n> Any Coagulopathy ( Prolonged PT> 15sec.):\n  o Inj. Konakion 10 mg\n    1 amp I/V slowly stat &once daily for 5days\n\n> Treatment of any underlying cause:\n  o Tab. Cavir 0.5 / Barcavir 0.5mg (HBsAg +ve)\n    0+0+1 (if compensated CLD) [if decompensated CLD then Cavir 1 mg daily]\n\n"}, {"title": "CLD Hepatic Encephalopathy", "keywords": ["cld", "hepatic", "encephalopathy"], "content": "\n> Treatment of complications:\n\nSpontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis: (Abdominal tenderness, Absent bowel sound)\n  - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1g\n    1 vial I/V Stat &8 Hourly\n\nHepatic encephalopathy: (See the Management below)\n\n--- Management of Hepatic encephalopathy ---\n\no Diet: Semisolid to Liquid; High Carbohydrate [If Unconscious: NG Feeding, If Severe: NPO TFO]\no Inf. 5%DNS 1000ml\n  I/V @ 20 d/min - daily\no Inj. Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Konakion 10 mg\n  1 amp I/V slowly stat &once daily for 5days\no Tab. Rifagut 550 mg\n  1+1+1\no Tab. Motigut 10mg / Omidon 10mg\n  1+1+1 (B/M)\no Syp. Avolac/ Osmolax\n  4-5 TSF TDS\no Syp. Lola / Hepagurd\n  1 sachet mixed with 1 glass water TDS\no Fleet Enema / Enema simplex\n  1 bottle P/R stat (If severe constipation not responding with above treatment)\n\n* No paracetamol, No NSAID, No Sedative, OPOIDS, Antidepressant, No Diuretics, No Anti-TB, No Anti-Fungal.\no Treatment of any precipitating cause eg-Infection,Constipation, Dehydration, Electrolyte imbalance\n\n> If signs of Cerebral Oedema (Headache, Vomiting, Confusion):\n  o Inj Osmosol 20%\n    300ml I/V running stat\n\n> If deep jaundice and itching present:\n  o Tab. Ursocol 300mg\n    1+0+1\n\n--- Management of Variceal Bleeding ---\n\no NPO TFO (except medication)\no Hartsol (1L)+ Inf 5% DNS (1L) (Take H/O DM before glucose containing fluid)\n  I/V @ 20 d/min\no Inj. Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Konakion 10 mg\n  1 amp I/V slowly stat &once daily for 5days\no Inj. Varipress 1mg/ Terlipressin (Contraindicated in severe IHD &peripheral vascular Disease)\n  2 amp. I/V slowly stat over 5 min & 6 hourly (Until bleeding stop)\no Blood Transfusion if required\no Urgent Endoscopy & Variceal ligation\n\n> After Variceal ligation add:\n  o Tab. Indever 40mg\n    1+0+1 [If BP is Low eg < 100/60mm or Pulse < 60/min then, 1/2 + 0 + 1/2]\n\n"}, {"title": "Variceal Bleeding", "keywords": ["variceal", "bleeding"], "content": "\n--- Treatment of Bleeding PUD ---\n\n(Hematemesis/ Maeelena + upper abdominal pain, H/O NSAIDs intake)\n\no NPO TFO (except medication)\no Hartsol (1L)+ Inf 5% DNS (1L) (Take H/O DM before glucose containing fluid)\n  I/V @ 20 d/min\no Inj Omeprazole/ Seclo 40mg, 2 vial in each liter of saline\n  I/V @ 20 d/ min daily\no Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n  2 vial I/V Stat\no Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\no Inj. Anadol 100mg\n  1 amp I/M Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Algin / Norvis 5 mg\n  1amp. I/V stat & 8 hourly\no Syp. Ulrif / Gastalfer\n  2 tsf TDS\no Check for Pulse, BP, Urine output regularly\no Blood Transfusion if required\no Urgent Endoscopy & Variceal ligation\n\n> Whenever acute condition is resolved then during discharge consider:\n  o Tab. Ulrif / Gastalfer 500mg\n    2+2+2+2 --------------- 1 month (Before Meal)\n  o Syp. Maganta plus\n    2 tsf TDS --------------- 1 month (After Meal)\n  o Pylotrip strip\n    1 strip at morning and 1 strip at night (Before meal) ------- 14 days\n  o Cap. Nexum 20 (After Finishing Pylotrip)\n    1+0+1 ------------------- Next 14 days\n\n"}, {"title": "Bleeding PUD", "keywords": ["bleeding", "pud"], "content": "\n--- Bleeding from any body orifice ---\n\n(Hemoptysis/ Hematemesis/ Per Rectal Bleeding/ Hematuria)\n\nHistory and Clinical features:\no Check Anaemia, Pulse, BP, Peripheral temperature (to exclude shock)\n\nInvestigations:\no Blood grouping & Rh typing\no CBC, Urea, Creatinine, SGPT\no PT, APTT\no Hemoptysis -> CXR P/A view, X-ray PNS, Sputum for AFB/ Malignant cell (According to features of TB/Malignancy)\no Hematemesis/ Melena -> Urgent endoscopy (After stabilization of the patient)\no Fresh P/R Bleeding -> Colonoscopy (After stabilization of the patient)\n\n> Treatment:\no Diet: 01/NPO in case of Hematemesis/ Melena/ Acute abdomen)\no Inf. N/S (1L) + Hartsol (2 L) + Inf 5% DNS (1L)\n  I/V @ 30 d/min\no Inj. Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg (Dose is different in bleeding PUD->see previous topic)\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\no Inj. Xamic / Traxyl/ Frabex 500mg (Tranexamic acid) [Alternative: Inj. Hemocon 1g I/V TDS]\n  1 amp I/V stat &TDS\no Record vitals (Pulse, BP, Urine output) regularly\no Treatment of underlying cause: oesophageal varrices, bleeding PUD (See previous topic)\no Blood Transfusion where required.\no Treatment of any complication: Shock (Fluid resuscitation, Dopamin Infusion)\n\n"}, {"title": "Bleeding Hemoptysis Hematemesis", "keywords": ["bleeding", "hemoptysis", "hematemesis"], "content": "\n--- MANAGEMENT OF UNCOMPLICATED/ LOWER UTI ---\n(NO HIGH FEVER OR VOMITING)\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - Diet: 01 (Normal)\no Urine R/M/E                  - Tab. Nitrofurantoin/ Ofuran SR / Nintosin SR 100mg\no Urine for C/S                  1+0+1 (A/M)\no S. Creatinine                - Tab. Paracetamol 500mg\no RBS                            1+1+1+1 (A/M)\no X-ray KUB                    - Cap. Omeprazole 20mg\n                                  1+0+1 (B/M)\n                                - Syp. Citra -K / Urikal\n                                  1 tsf in 1/2 glass water TDS\n\nNitrofurantoin is not used in Renal Impairment, So In Case of Renal Impairment:\n  - Tab. Cefuroxime 500mg 1+0+1\n\n--- MANAGEMENT OF ACUTE PYELONEPHRITIS ---\n(High Fever, Severe AbdominalPain, Vomiting)\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - Diet: 01 (Normal)\no Urine R/M/E                  - Inf. N/S 1L\no Urine for C/S                  I/V @ 10 drops/min stat & daily\no S. Creatinine                - Inj. Cefuroxime 750mg/ Cefotil/ Furocef\no S. Electrolytes                1 vial I/V Stat & 8 Hourly\no RBS                          - Inj Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\no USG of KUB                     1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no X-ray KUB                    - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n                                  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\nDaily Follow-Up:               - Inj Anadol 100mg\no Temperature                    1 amp I/M Stat & 12 hourly\no Urine Output                 - Inj Algin / Norvis 5 mg\no Respiratory rate               1amp. I/V stat & 8 hourly\no BP                           - Tab. Paracetamol 500mg\no Pulse                          1+1+1+1 (A/M) (If patient has profuse vomiting and\no GCS                            can't take orally add paracetamol suppository instead of oral)\n\n"}, {"title": "UTI Pyelonephritis", "keywords": ["uti", "pyelonephritis"], "content": "\n> Discharge of acute pyelonephritis:\n  o Tab. Cefuroxime 500mg / Cefotil 500mg\n    1+0+1 --------------- total 14 Days (Total means hospital duration + discharge duration)\n  - Tab. Paracetamol 500mg\n    1+1+1+1 (A/M) ---- if Fever\n  o Tab. Algin / Norvis 50mg\n    1+0+1 --------------- if pain\n  o Cap. Omeprazole 20mg / Seclo 20mg\n    1+0+1 (B/M) ------ 15 days\n  o Tab. Citra -K / Urikal\n    1 tsf in 1/2 glass water TDS\n\n--- Management of AKI ---\n\no Diet: 01 (or NPO if severe vomiting)\n  o Total fluid intake = Previous day urine output + 500 ml\n  o Protein restricted, salt restricted\n  o Fruit & fruit juice restricted\no Inf. Normal saline / 5% DNS (1L) (If pt has Dehydration or in NPO)\n  I/V @ 10 d/min daily\no Inj. Ceftriaxone / Ceftron 1 gm\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg (Dose is different in bleeding PUD->see previous topic)\n  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\no Continuous catheterization\no Maintain intake & output chart\n\nIn case of urosepsis:\n  o Inj. Meropen/Spechac 500mg (instead of ceftriaxone)\n    1 vial I/V stat and 8 hourly\n\nTreatment of any Precipitating condition/ Associated condition/ Complication:\no Inj. Lasix 20mg/ Fusid (Fluid overload/ Pulmonary oedema [HF])\n  1 amp I/V stat & bd (8 am, 4 pm) - Increased dose may be used if required.\no Treatment of shock if present: (discussed earlier)\no Treatment of Hyperkaliemia: (discussed later)\n\n"}, {"title": "AKI Acute Kidney Injury", "keywords": ["aki", "acute", "kidney", "injury"], "content": "\n--- Management of CKD ---\n\no Diet: 01 (or NPO if severe vomiting)\n  o Total fluid intake = Previous day urine output + 500 ml\n  o Protein restricted, salt restricted\n  o Fruit & fruit juice restricted\no Tab Calbotol (Or. Dicalttrol plus)\n  0+1+0\no Cap. Omeprazole 20mg / Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (B/M)\no Tab. Omidon 10mg/ Motigut\n  2+2+2 (B/M)\no Tab. Fusid 40 mg (If leg edema / Fluid overload)\n  1+0+0\no Tab. Hypophos 667mg (If hyperphosphatemia)\n  1+0+1\n\nTreatment of any Precipitating condition/ Associated condition/ Complication:\n  - Inj. Lasix 20mg/ Fusid (Fluid overload/ Pulmonary oedema [HF])\n    1 amp I/V stat & bd (8 am, 4 pm) - Increased dose may be used if required.\n  - Treatment of shock if present: (discussed earlier)\n  - Treatment of Hyperkaliemia: (discussed later)\n\n> If hypertension present:\n  o Tab. Amdocal 5mg/ Camlodin\n    1+0+0 (may be increased upto 10mg daily)\nIf still not controlled then add:\n  o Tab. Alphapress 1mg (Prazosin)\n    1+1+1 (may be increased upto 18mg daily)\nIf still not controlled then add:\n  o Tab. Bisocor/Bisoprolol 2.5mg\n    1+0+0 (may be increased upto 5-10mg daily)\n\n> If Metabolic Acidosis present:\n  o Tab. Sodicarb 600mg\n    1+1+1\n\n"}, {"title": "CKD Chronic Kidney Disease", "keywords": ["ckd", "chronic", "kidney", "disease"], "content": "\n> If DM present:\n  o Control by -Insulin (Maxsulin/ Ansulin), Linatab/Linita (described earlier)\n\n> If any source of infection:\n  o Tab Cefuroxime (Cefotil 500mg bd) or Ceftriaxone 1gm (Ceftron)\n\n> If anaemia present:\n  - Blood transfusion (If Hb% <8g/dl)\n  - Iron injection or oral iron supplement (If low S. ferritin/ Transferrin saturation)\n  - Inj. Erythropoietin/ Eporen. (If No other cause found/ Ferritin is normal)\n\n> If hyperkalaemia present: (Described later)\n  o Tab. Sodicarb 600mg\n    1+1+1\n\n--- Management of severe symptomatic hyponatraemia ---\n\n(S. Na+<124 mmol/l plus CNS symptoms e.g: confusion, convulsion, coma)\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - Diet: 01 (Normal) [NG feeding if patient is unconscious]\no S. Electrolyte                  Added salt - 1 tsf mixed with meals 3 times daily\no S. Creatinine                - Inf. 3% NaCl (500ml)\no RBS                            I/V @ 32 microdrops/min stat then,\n                                - Inf. N/S 1L\nOthers to find etiology:         I/V @ 20 drops/min stat & daily\n(According To Clinical Suspicion)- Tab. NaCl (300mg)\no X-ray Chest P/A view           2+2+2+2\no ECG                          - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\no Urine R/M/E                    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Urine for C/S                - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\no S. Lipase                      1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\no USG of W/A\no Endoscopy of upper GIT       o Must use microburette set during infusion of 3% NaCl.\no CT scan of brain              o Write \"microdrops\" in word rather than using symbol \"udrops\"\n\no Avoid diuretics & other drugs that can be responsible.\no Check S. Electrolyte regularly.\no Treat the underlying cause.\no Further treatment protocol should be guided by serum electrolyte level.\n\n> If there is convulsion, Add:\n  o Inj. Barbit 200mg\n    1 Amp I/M Stat & BD\n\nNote:\no Hyponatraemia = Serum sodium level<135 mmol/L\no Severe hyponatraemia = Serum sodium level< 124mmol/L\no Slow correction is always safer.\no For proper correction there are online apps that contain formula and give you correct fluid rate.\n  (not discussed here, gross estimated formula is applied here)\n\n--- Management of Mild & Moderate /Chronic Asymptomatic Hyponatraemia ---\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - Diet: 01 (Normal)\no S. Electrolyte                  Added salt - 1 tsf mixed with meals 3 times daily\no S. Creatinine                - Inf. N/S 2L\no RBS                            I/V @ 20 drops/min stat &\n                                - Inf. N/S 1L\nOthers to find etiology:         I/V @ 20 drops/min daily\n(According To Clinical Suspicion)- Tab. NaCl (300mg)\no X-ray Chest P/A view           2+2+2+2\no ECG                          - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\no Urine R/M/E                    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Urine for C/S                - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\no S. Lipase                      1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\no USG of W/A\no Endoscopy of upper GIT\no CT scan of brain\n\no Avoid diuretics & other drugs that can be responsible.\no Check S. Electrolyte regularly.\no Treat the underlying cause.\no Further treatment protocol should be guided by serum electrolyte level.\n\n"}, {"title": "Hyponatraemia", "keywords": ["hyponatraemia"], "content": "\n--- Management of Hyperkalaemia ---\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - Diet: 01 (Normal)\no S. Electrolyte                  Fruit and fruit juice restriction\no S. Creatinine                - Nebulization with windel plus\no RBS                            stat & 6 hourly\no Blood urea                   - Inf. 5% DA1L\n\nOthers to find etiology:         Inj. Maxsulin-R (100IU) - 10 units\n(According To Clinical Suspicion) I/V @ 30 drops/min daily\n                                - Norme-K sachet\n                                  1 sachete in 1 glass water TDS for 3 days\n                                - Inj. Calcium gluconate 10% (10ml) (If K+ >6.5 mmol/l)\n                                  1 amp I/V slowly over 10 min stat\n                                - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n                                  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n                                - Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\n                                  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\n\no If all fails refer to dialysis unit (nephrology).\no Treat the underlying cause.\no Check S. Electrolyte regularly.\no Further treatment protocol should be guided by serum electrolyte level.\n\n> If S. Creatinine Normal, Add:\n  o Inj. Lasix\n    1 Amp. I/V Stat & BD - (8am, 4pm)\n  o Inf. N/S 1L\n    I/V @ 20 drops/min\n\n> If Metabolic acidosis (HCO3- < 18 mmol/L), Add:\n  o Inj. Sodib 7.5% 25ml\n    1 vial I/V slowly stat\n\n"}, {"title": "Hyperkalaemia", "keywords": ["hyperkalaemia"], "content": "\n--- Management of Hypokalaemia ---\n\nSEVERE HYPOKALAEMIA\n(Serum K+<2.5 mmol/L)\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - Diet: 01 (Normal)\no S. Electrolyte                  Fruit and fruit juice intake\no S. Creatinine                   Green coconut water\no RBS                          - Inf. N/S 1L\n                                  +\nOthers to find etiology:         Inj. KT 2 Amp,\n(According To Clinical Suspicion) I/V @ 20 drops/min stat (Can be repeated if serum K+\n                                  remain < 2.5 mmol/l)\n                                - Syp. KT\n                                  2 TSF with 1/2 glass water TDS\n\no Treat the underlying cause.\no Check S. Electrolyte regularly.\no Further treatment protocol should be guided by serum electrolyte level.\n\nMODERATE HYPOKALAEMIA\n(Serum K+ 2.5-2.9 mmol/L)\n\nRx on admission:\n- Diet: 01 (Normal)\n  Fruit and fruit juice intake\n  Green coconut water\n- Syp. KT\n  2 TSF with 1/2 glass water TDS\n\nMILD HYPOKALAEMIA\n(Serum K+ 3.0-3.5 mmol/L)\n\nRx on admission:\n- Diet: 01 (Normal)\n  Fruit and fruit juice intake\n  Green coconut water\n- Syp. KT (If cant take adequate fruit or ongoing loss)\n  2 TSF with 1/2 glass water TDS\n\n"}, {"title": "Hypokalaemia", "keywords": ["hypokalaemia"], "content": "\n--- Management of OPC Poisoning ---\nSEVERE OPC POISONING\n\nClinical Features:\no H/O Vomiting, Diarrhoea, Profuse Sweating, Urinary Incontinance\no Altered Consciousness\no Pinpoint pupils\no Lung: Creps (++)\no Systolic BP < 80 mmHg\no Pulse < 60 bpm\n\n> Treatment:\n  - NPO TFO\n  - O2 inhalation 4-6 /min (If Respiratory distress)\n  - Inf. Normal Saline (1L)+ 5% DNS (1L)+ Hartsol (1L)\n    I/V @ 30 d/ min daily\n  - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm\n    1 vial IV stat & 12 hourly\n  - Inj. Atropine\n    5 amp I/V stat & then\n    10 amp I/V after 15 min then\n    20 amp I/V after next 15 min thus\n    Doubling the dose at 15 min interval until Full Atropinization (see below)\n  - Inj. Pradox 1 gm\n    1 vial I/V slowly stat (over 4 min) & 8 hourly\n  - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\n    1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\n  - Continuous catheterization\n  - Check Pulse, BP, Pupils, lung, axilla at 15 min interval (at least 1/2 hourly)\n\nSigns of full Atropinization: (All five criterias to be fulfilled)\n  o Pupils: Full dilated\n  o Pulse > 80 b/min\n  o Systolic BP > 80 mm Hg\n  o Lungs: Clear\n  o Axilla: Hot and Dry\n\n"}, {"title": "OPC Poisoning Organophosphate", "keywords": ["opc", "poisoning", "organophosphate"], "content": "\n> If patient become restless & pupils are full dilated, bight may be there is over atropinization then, Add:\n  o Inj. Sedil 10 mg\n    1 vial I/V slowly stat (Also consider about tappering of Atropine - See below)\n\nMaintenance dose / Tapering of atropine:\no When signs of Atropinizations are present then calculate total dose of atropine required for atropinization.\no Administer 50% of total dose of atropine in next 24 hours divided in 3L saline (15% in each 1L saline) for maintenance of atropine.\no For example:\n  - 1 patient got atropinization at 40 amp atropine.\n  - So, total dose required for atropinization: 5 amp + 10amp + 20amp + 40amp = total 75amp atropine.\n  - 50% of 75 amp atropine = 37 amp (approximately) = 12 amp x 3)\n  - So order to be given as below-\n    o Inf. N/S (1L)+ Inf 5% DNS (1L)+ Inf H/S (1L)\n      Inj. Atropine 12amp in each 1L saline\n      I/V @ 30 d/min\n\nMILD TO MODERATE OPC POISONING\n\nClinical Features:\no Clean cut history, Symptoms/evidence of OPC\no But no signs of severe opc poisoning e.g:\n  - Pupils: Not pinpoint\n  - Pulse > 80 bpm\n  - Systolic BP>80 mmHg\n  - Lungs: Clear\n\n> Treatment of Mild to Moderate OPC Poisoning:\n  - NPO TFO\n  - Inf. Normal Saline (1L)+ 5% DNS (1L)+ Hartsol (1L)\n    I/V @ 30 d/ min daily\n  - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm\n    1 vial IV stat & 12 hourly\n  - Inj. Atropine\n    2 amp I/V stat & then\n    4 amp I/V after 15 min then\n    8 amp I/V after next 15 min thus\n    Doubling the dose at 15 min interval until Full Atropinization (see below)\n  - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n    1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n  - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\n    1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\n  - Continuous catheterization\n  - Check Pulse, BP, Pupils, lung, axilla at 15 min interval (at least 1/2 hourly)\n\n--- SUSPECTED OPC POISONING ---\n\nNote following points:\no No clear cut signs / symptoms of OPC.\no But there is possibility of OPC poisoning.\n\nDo Challenge Test as following:\nCheck baseline pulse rate & then administer:\n  - Inj. Atropine\n    2 amp I/V stat\n\nAgain check pulserate after 5-10 min.\no If pulse rate is increased >=25 b/min by this time then it is not a case of OPC & no further atropine is required.\no But, if pulse rate do not increased 20-25 b/min then administer further dose of atropine & follow up.\n\n--- Management of Sedative poisoning/ Street poisoning /Unknown poisoning ---\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no ECG                          - NPO TFO\no S. Electrolytes including    - O2 inhalation 4-6 /min (If Respiratory distress)\n  HCO3- (HCO3- specially      - Inf. Normal Saline (1L)+ 5% DNS (1L)+ Hartsol (1L)\n  important for Amitriptyline    I/V @ 30 d/ min daily\n  Poisoning)                   - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm\no S. Creatinine                  1 vial IV stat & 12 hourly\no SGPT                         - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\no RBS                            1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no CBC with ESR                 - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\no Urine R/E                      1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\no Chest X-ray P/A View         - Inj. Lasix/Fusid (If Systolic BP >= 110 mmHg)\n                                  1 amp I/V stat &BD (8 am, 4 pm)\n                                - Continuous catheterization (If Unconscious)\n\nIn addition to above management add specific Mx for sedative when appropriate:\n\nBenzodiazepine (Clonazepam/ Diazepam)\n\nUse specific Antidote Flumazenil as below if:\no Patient is in Coma\no Respiratory Distress and reduced consciousness.\n\nGive order of Flumazenil:\n  - Inj Flumazenil/ Anexate 0.5mg/ 5ml [Contraindicated in Seizure/ Epilepsy or when co-ingested TCA (Amitriptyline)]\n    1 amp I/V slowly stat over 5min\n\nIf no response and patient is in coma/ severe respiratory distress:\n  o Call to ICU\n\n"}, {"title": "Sedative Poisoning Unknown Poisoning", "keywords": ["sedative", "poisoning", "unknown", "poisoning"], "content": "\nTCA (Amitriptyline)\n\nUse specific Antidote Flumazenil as below if:\no Hospital admission is recommended for ingestion of >=5mg/kg\no 10-20mg/kg can be life threatening\no Use Sodi-bi-carb I/V solution as below if:\n  - Wide QRS (> 116ms/ 4mm)\n  - Prolonged QT\n  - Cardiac Arrythmia\n  - Metabolic Acidosis\n\no Inj. Sodib 7.5% (25ml)\n  2 vial (50ml) I/V @ 30d/min stat\n\n--- Management of Herpic or Savion Poisoning/ Corrosive Agent/ Rat killer Poisoning ---\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no ECG                          - NPO TFO\no S. Electrolytes including    - O2 inhalation 4-6 /min (If Respiratory distress)\n  HCO3-                        - Inf. Normal Saline (1L)+ 5% DNS (1L)+ Hartsol (1L)\no S. Creatinine                  I/V @ 30 d/ min daily\no SGPT                         - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm\no RBS                            1 vial IV stat & 12 hourly\no CBC with ESR                 - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\no Urine R/E                      1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\no Chest X-ray P/A View         - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\no Blood Grouping & Rh typing     1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\n                                - Continuous catheterization (If Unconscious)\nIn rat-killer poisoning:        - Blood Transfusion (If severe Bleeding with\n- Prothrombin time with INR       Hypotension/ Anaemia)\n  (as it contains Warfarin like - Treatment of the specific cause when appropriate\n  agent)                          [see below]\n\nIn Herpic or Savlon / Corrosive\nagent ingestion patients:\n  - Urgent Endoscopy (Within\n    24 hours of Ingestion to see any\n    Esophageal\n    ulceration/perforation)\n\n"}, {"title": "Corrosive Poisoning Rat Killer", "keywords": ["corrosive", "poisoning", "rat", "killer"], "content": "\n> In Herpic or Savlon / Corrosive Agent if oesophageal perforation:\n  o Refer patient to cardiothoracic surgeon for surgery (After resuscitation including fluid & blood transfusion)\n\n> In Rat-Killer Poisoning if PT is Prolonged then add:\n  o Inj. Konakion 10mg\n    1 amp I/V slowly stat & once daily for 5 days\n\n--- Management of paracetamol poisoning ---\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no CBC with ESR                  - NPO TFO\no S. Bilirubin                 - Inf. 5% DNS (2L)\no SGPT                           I/V @ 30 d/ min daily\no Prothrombin time             - Activated charcoal (if comes within 1 hour of ingestion)\no S. Electrolytes including       50gm mixed with 200ml water\n  HCO3-                        - Inj. Ceftriaxone 1 gm\no S. Creatinine                  1 vial IV stat & 12 hourly\no RBS                          - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n                                  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n                                - Inj Emistat / Ofran 8 mg (if H/O Vomiting)\n                                  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly\n                                - Inf. 5% DA 200ml+\n                                  Inj. N-Acetylcystein 1gm\n                                  9 amp I/V @ running stat\n                                  Then,\n                                - Inf. 5% DA 500ml+\n                                  Inj. N-Acetylcystein 1gm\n                                  6 amp I/V @ 30d/min stat\n                                  Then,\n                                - Inf. 5% DA 500ml+\n                                  Inj. N-Acetylcystein 1gm\n                                  3 amp I/V @ 20d/min stat\n                                - Regular monitoring of RBS, urine output, any\n                                  bleeding or development of jaundice\n\no NAC can cause hypersensitivity reaction (rash, hypotension, angioedema, bronchospasm) & stop nac immediately and should be treated with Inj. Chlorpheniramine/Avil, Inj. Cotson\n\n"}, {"title": "Paracetamol Poisoning", "keywords": ["paracetamol", "poisoning"], "content": "\n> If injection N-Acetylcystein (NAC) is not available then use oral NAC as below:\n  o Mucomist DT / Alistin 600mg / N-Acetylcysteine\n    14 tablets stat (mixing with 200ml fruitjuice or soft drink)\n  Then,\n  o Mucomist DT / Alistin 600mg / N-Acetylcysteine\n    7 tablets 4 hourly for total 17 doses (mixing with 100ml fruit juice or soft drink)\n\no Diluted solutions of NAC should be freshly prepared and used within 1 hour.\no If any dose vomited within 1 hour of administration should be repeated.\n\nNote:\nFatal dose of paracetamol:\n  o 12gm (24 tablets) or 150mg/kg\n\nIndications of Antidote (N-Acetylcystein):\no Single overdose of more than 12g or 150mg/kg.\no A high risk patient ingested more than 75mg/kg.\no A patient presents more than 8 hours after single overdose and is symptomatic (vomiting, right hypochondriac pain).\no A child ingested more than 90mg/kg.\n\n> If hepatic failure develops: Management is as like as previous except addition of vitamin K, Mannitol and reducing dose of NAC-\n  o Inj. Konakion 10mg\n    6 amp I/V stat\n  o Inj. Mannitol 20% 300ml\n    I/V @ running (if cerebral oedema /encephalopathy present)\n  o Inf. 5% DA (500ml)+\n    Inj. N-Acetylcystein 1gm\n    6 amp I/V 15 drops/min (over 8 hours)\n  o Inf. 10% DA (2L)\n    I/V @ 30 drops/min\n\no If renal failure develops, haemodialysis may be needed\no Liver transplantation is the choice in case of hepatic failure with poorer outcome\n\n--- Management of venomous snake bite ---\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx on admission:\no Do 20 minutes whole blood     - Diet - 01 (Normal) [NG feeding if dysphagia due to bulbar\n  coagulation test (WBCT) for     palsy]\n  every patient.               - Inj. Adrenaline 1ml (0.1%)\n                                  3/4 amp (0.25ml) s/c stat\n                                - Inj. Polyvalent antivenom (AV) (1 vial=10 ml N/S)\n                                  Total 10vials=100 ml solution\n                                  + 100 ml N/S=200ml\n                                  I/V@200 microdrops/minstat.\n                                - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n                                  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n                                - Inj. TT\n                                  1 amp I/M in one arm\n                                - Inj. TIG\n                                  1 amp I/M in another arm.\n\n                                If neuro-toxic signs present then also add -\n                                - Inj. Atropine 0.6 mg\n                                  1 amp I/V Stat\n                                - Inj. Neos-R 0.5 mg /Neostigmine\n                                  2 1/2amp I/M Stat\n\no Atropine & neostigmine can be maintained 4 hourly if respiratory failure/ severe persistent neurotoxic signs are present.\no Atropine must be given prior to neostigmine.\no Subcutaneous adrenaline may not given to patient with high BP/ known hypertensive.\no Atropine & neostigmine given only for neurotoxic manifestation.\no Call to ICU for patient with neurologic feature as she/he may develop respiratory distress.\no Antivenom may be repeated 1-2 hours after completion of previous dose in neurotoxic case (for maximum 2 further doses) & 6 hours in haematotoxic case.\n\n"}, {"title": "Snake Bite", "keywords": ["snake", "bite"], "content": "\n> Management when anaphylaxis:\n  o Inj. Adrenaline (0.1%) 1ml\n    1/2 amp (0.5ml) I/M stat\n  o Inj. Cotson 100mg\n    1 vial I/V stat\n  o Inj. Avil (chlorpheniramine)\n    1 amp I/M stat\n\nWhen to use antivenom:\n\nSuspected/confirmed snake bite with following features:\no Systemic envenomation:\n  - Neurological feature:\n    * Ptosis\n    * External ophthalmoplegia\n    * Broken neck sign\n    * Dysphagia\n    * Nasal regurgitation\n    * Respiratory distress (diaphragmatic muscle paralysis)\n  - Haematological:\n    * Coagulopathy (WBCT>20 min)\n    * Bleeding manifestation\n  - Renal failure\n  - Heart failure\n  - DIC\n  - Arrhythmia\n\no Local envenomation:\n  - Rapid development of swelling (without ligature).\n  - Swelling of half of the bitten limb (without ligature) within 48 hours of bite.\n  - Tender local lymph node enlargement.\n\n--- Management of Non-venomous snake bite ---\n\n- Diet: Liquid\n- Inf. Normal Saline (1L)\n  I/V @ 20 d/ min\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n\nIf there is any bite mark then add -\n  - Inj. TT\n    1 amp I/M in one arm\n  - Inj. TIG\n    1 amp I/M in another arm.\n\no Counsel this patient about the neurotoxic and hematotoxic feature and tell if he/she develop one/more of these features antivenom should be given\no Observe the patient for 24-48 hours.\n\n--- Management of Electric Burn/ Electric Shock ---\n\nInvestigation:                  At first check Vitals esp. Pulse, BP to exclude cardiac\no ECG (Must to exclude            arrhythmia, hypotension.\n  cardiac arrhythmia)\no S. Electrolytes including    Rx on admission:\n  HCO3-                        - Diet - 01 (Normal)\no S. Creatinine                - Inf. Normal Saline (1L)\no SGPT                           I/V @ 15 d/min\no RBS                          - Cap. Omeprazole/Seclo 20mg/ In severe burn Inj.\no Chest X-ray P/A View           Omeprazole 40mg I/V 12hourly\n                                  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n                                - Cap. Flucloxacillin/ Phylopen 500mg [In severe burn,\n                                  Inj. Fluclox 500mg I/V 6hourly]\n                                  1+1+1+1\n                                - Tab. Paracetamol (500mg)\n                                  2+2+2 (A/M)\n                                - Burna cream\n                                  Apply over burned area 4-6 times daily\n\no Check Pulse, BP and urine output to exclude cardiac arrhythmia, hypotension, AKI.\no Treatment of complications if any eg: cardiac arrhythmia, Electrolyte imbalance, AKI.\no In severe burn, call to dept. of plastic surgery for better management.\n\n"}, {"title": "Non-venomous Snake Bite Electric Burn", "keywords": ["non-venomous", "snake", "bite", "electric", "burn"], "content": "\n> If severe pain then Add -\n  o Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n    1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\n  o Inj. Anadol 100mg (Try to avoid NSAIDs as these may increase the chance of developing AKI)\n    1 amp I/M Stat & 12 hourly\n\n--- Management of Bee Sting/ Wasp Bite ---\n\nInvestigation (All Routines):   Rx on admission:\no S. Creatinine                - Diet - 01 (Normal)\no S. Electrolytes              - Inj. Normal Saline (2L) [In mild to moderate case 1L]\no SGPT                           I/V @ 20 d/ min\no ECG                          - Inj. Cefuroxime / Cefotil (750mg) [Oral if mild/moderate]\no CXR P/A view (If any          1 vial I/V stat & 8 hourly\n  shortness of breath)         - Inj. Cotson (100mg) [Oral if mild/moderate]\no S. CPK (In extensive bee       1 vial I/V stat & 8 hourly\n  bites to exclude             - Inj. Avil [Oral if mild/moderate]\n  Rhabdomyolysis)                1 vial I/M stat\n                                - Inj. Anadol 100mg\n                                  1 amp I/M Stat &8 hourly\n                                - Inj. Omeprazole /Seclo 40mg\n                                  1 vial I/V Stat & 12 hourly\n                                - Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n                                  1 amp I/V stat & 8 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\n                                - Tab. Paracetamol (500mg)\n                                  2+2+2 (A/M)\n                                - Tab. Histacin\n                                  1+0+1\n                                - Calamine lotion (If severe itching)\n                                  Apply locally 3 times daily\n                                - Check Pulse, BP and Urine output regularly\n\nIf patient develops anaphylactic shock then add -\n  o Inj. Adrenaline (0.1%) 1ml\n    1/2 amp (0.5ml) I/M stat\n\n"}, {"title": "Bee Sting Wasp Bite", "keywords": ["bee", "sting", "wasp", "bite"], "content": "\no Before starting above treatments, at first check vitals especially pulse, BP, urine output to exclude anaphylactic shock. If vitals are stable (Not in shock) then give above treatment.\no If patient is in shock treat as Anaphylactic shock (Discussed earlier)\no Try to avoid NSAIDs as these may increase the chance of developing AKI.\n\n--- Management of Low Back Pain (LBP) ---\nMODERATE TO SEVERE LBP\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx of moderate to severe LBP on admission:\no All Routine                  - Diet - 01 (Normal)\no X-Ray L/S Spine B/V          - Inj. Ketorolac 30mg (Contraindicated in Renal disease,\no MRI of L/S Spine               COPD/BA, Bleeding PUD)\n                                  1 amp I/M Stat& 8 Hourly\nIf Seronegative Spondylitis is - Inj Tramadol (100mg)/Anadol)\nSuspected (Tenderness of SI      1 amp I/M Stat & 12 Hourly\nJoint, Young, E/H +ve):       - Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n  - CRP                          1 amp I/V stat &12 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\n  - X-Ray pelvis including     - Tab. Beclofen 10mg/Flexibac/ Beklo/ Flexilax\n    both SI Joint                 1+0+1\n  - HLA-B27                    - Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n                                  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n\n                                If There is any Radiculopathy (Pain radiating from back to\n                                knee or below) then also add -\n                                - Cap. Pregabelin 50mg/ Pregaba/ Prelica/ Neurolin\n                                  1+0+1 (May be increased upto 75mg BD after 7 days)\n                                If still not settled then add -\n                                - Tab. Amitriptylin 25mg/ Amilin/ Tryptin\n                                  0+0+1/2 (May be increased upto 25mg OD after 7 days)\n\nIndication of MRI of L/S Spine:\n1. LBP with severe radiculopathy.\n2. LBP with bladder or bowel involvement e.g. Urinary retention.\n3. LBP Neurological Deficit e.g. absent jerks, muscle weakness,sensory loss.\n\n"}, {"title": "Low Back Pain LBP Osteoporosis", "keywords": ["low", "back", "pain", "lbp", "osteoporosis"], "content": "\nMILD TO MODERATE LBP\n\n> Treatment of Mild to Moderate LBP on Admission/ Discharge Medication of Severe LBP (Improved):\n\n  o Tab. Naproxen 500mg/ Naprosyn\n    1+0+1 (After Meal)\n  o Tab. Beclofen 10mg/Flexibac/ Beklo/ Flexilax\n    1+0+1\n  o Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n    1+0+1 (Before meal)\n  o Inj. Anadol 100mg (Try to avoid NSAIDs as these may increase the chance of developing AKI)\n    1 amp I/M Stat & 12 hourly\n\nIf There is any radiculopathy (Pain radiating from back to knee or below) then also add -\n  o Cap. Pregabelin 50mg/ Pregaba/ Prelica/ Neurolin\n    1+0+1 (May be increased upto 75mg BD after 7 days)\n  o Tab. Neuro-B\n    1+0+1\n\nIf still not settled then add -\n  o Tab. Amitriptylin 25mg/ Amilin/ Tryptin\n    0+0+1/2 (May be increased upto 25mg OD after 7 days)\n\nIf Osteoporotic fracture then -\n  o Tab. Maxbon 150mg (Ibandronic Acid) (Contraindicated in GERD patients)\n    1 tab. P/O Stat & Monthly for 12months (1 hour before meal, take with 1 glass water & in sitting position, walk for 15-30min after taking, don't lie down within 30min)\n  o Tab. Calbo-D\n    1+0+1\n\nIf low vitamin-D then add -\n  o Cap. D-Rise 20000IU\n    1 tab P/O Stat & then weekly for 6weeks\n\no In Renal disease/ COPD or Bronchial Asthma/ Bleeding PUD- Do not use NSAIDs (Ketorolac, Aceclofenac, Naproxen)\no Paracetamol (e.g; Tab Ace 500mg 2tab TDS) or Tramadol (Anadol) or Napadol / Pangesic 1 tab TDS can be used.\n\n"}, {"title": "Vertigo", "keywords": ["vertigo"], "content": "\n--- Management of Vertigo ---\nSEVERE VERTIGO WITH OR WITHOUT VOMITING\n\nInvestigation:                  Rx of moderate to severe LBP on admission:\no All Routines (CBC, RBS, S.   - Diet - 01 (Normal)\n  Creatinine, S.               - Inj. Vergon 5mg\n  Electrolytes, ECG, CXR P/A     1 amp I/M Stat& 8 Hourly\n  View)                        - Inj. Perkinil 5mg (Along with Inj. Vergon)\n                                  1 amp I/M Stat&12 Hourly\nIf Central (Cerebral/ Brainstem)- Tab Menaril 8mg\ncause is suspected-               1+0+1 (Before meal)\n  - MRI of Brain (If MRI is not- Inj. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n    available then CT Scan        1 amp I/V stat &12 hourly (if H/O Vomiting)\n    Brain)                     - Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n                                  1+0+1 (Before meal)\nIf Miners Disease is suspected:- Treatment of underlying cause if any\n  - Pure Tone Audiometry\n\nMILD TO MODERATE VERTIGO\n\n> Treatment of Mild to Moderate Vertigo on Admission/ Discharge Medication of Severe Peripheral Vertigo (Improved):\n\n  - Tab. Vergon / Stemetil 5mg\n    1+1+1\n  - Tab. Perkinil 5mg\n    1/2+0+1/2\n  - Tab. Menaril 8mg\n    1+0+1 (Before meal)\n  - Tab. Emistat / Ofran 8 mg\n    1+0+1 (Before meal) [if H/O Vomiting]\n  - Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n    1+0+1 (Before meal)\n  - Treatment of underlying cause if any\n\nClinical Evaluation of Vertigo\n\no Definition: Rotation of the head along with surroundings.\no Common Causes:\n    - Peripheral:\n        * Acute Labyrinthitis/ Vestibular neuritis: Sudden severe vertigo, vomiting,\n          unsteadiness, H/O Fever.\n        * BPPV: Vertigo with position change, Very brief recurrent attack.\n        * Meniere's disease: Tinnitus, Deafness/ Ear fullness.\n    - Central:\n        * Cerebellar lesion: Unsteadiness, Gait Problem.\n        * Brainstem lesion: Diplopia/ Vomiting\no Examinations:\n    - Cerebellar signs: Finger nose Test, Horizontal Nystagmus, Ataxic Gait.\n    - Brainstem signs: Pupil size, ocular movement, other cranial nerve exam esp VII, VIII, V.\n    - If Ear Problem: Rinne & Weber test.\n\nClinical Evaluation of Dizziness\n\no Definition: Rotation or Lightheadedness of head but no rotation of surrounding.\no Common Causes:\n    - Anaemia\n    - Hypotension/ Postural Hypotension/ Severe HTN\n    - Hyponatraemia/ Dehydration\n    - Hypoglycaemia\n    - Anxiety\n    - Pre-Syncope due to any cause:\n        * Cardiac causes:\n            checkmark Arrythmia (AF, Bradycardia)\n            checkmark Valvular Lesion (AS/ HOCM)\n            checkmark Heart Failure\n            checkmark Vasovagal syncope (due to prolonged standing/ Exercise)\no Examinations:\n    - Anaemia\n    - Pulse- Bradycardia, Irregular (AF)\n    - BP including Postular Hypotension\n    - Precordium auscultation- AS/ HOCM\n    - Carotid bruit\n\n"}, {"title": "Hiccup", "keywords": ["hiccup"], "content": "\nManagement of Hiccup\n\nCommon causes of Hiccup:\no Gastroesophageal Reflux Disease, PUD.\no Uraemia/ Renal failure.\no Electrolyte imbalance/ Metabolic Acidosis.\no Liver failure.\no Diaphragmatic Irritation due to any cause e.g: Hiatus Hernia, Sub phrenic Abscess.\no CNS cause: SAH, Stroke, Meningo-encephalitis.\n\n> Treatment of Hiccup:\n\nInvestigation:\no All Routines (CBC, RBS, S.\n  Creatinine, S. Electrolytes\n  including HCO3, Blood\n  Urea, ECG, CXR P/A View,\n  SGPT)\no USG W/A\n\nWhen Severe PUD is suspected:\no Endoscopy of upper GIT\n\nWhen Stroke or CNS Pathology is\nsuspected:\no CT Scan of Brain\n\nRx of moderate to severe LBP on admission:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n- Tab. Domperidon 10mg/ Omidion/ Moticut\n  1+1+1 (Before meal)\n- Tab. Beclofen 10mg/ Beklo/ Flexilax\n  1+1+1 (Before meal)\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Treatment of underlying cause if any\n- Drinking cool water\n- Breathing into a Re-breathing Mask\n\nIf GERD is suspected then add-\n    o Syp. Asynta / Gaviflux\n      2 tsf TDS (After meal)\n\nIf still Hiccup is not improved add-\n    Tab. Vergon / Stemetil 5mg\n    1+1+1\n    Tab. Perkinil 5mg\n    1/2+0+1/2\n\nIf still Hiccup is not improved add-\n    Tab. Vergon / Stemetil 5mg\n    1+1+1\n    o Tab. Perkinil 5mg\n      1+0+1\n\n"}, {"title": "Fever Approach", "keywords": ["fever", "approach"], "content": "\n> If intractable Hiccup not responding to above measures then omit Vergon & add:\n  Tab Largectil 25mg/ Opsonil /In Severe cases: Inj. Opsonil 50mg, 1/4 amp I/M stat/\n  1+0+1\n  Tab. Perkinil 5mg\n  1+0+1\n\nApproach to a patient with Fever\n\nHigh grade Short duration, usually history is < 2 weeks:\no Common causes:\n    - Typhoid fever                    - Dengue Fever/ Other Viral fever\n    - Typhus/ Rickettsial fever        - Any Pyogenic Infection/ Abscess- RTI, UTI, Lung\n    - Leptospirosis                      Abscess/ Liver Abscess.\n    - Malaria Fever\n\no Clinical evaluation:\n    - History:\n        * Points to be noted: Duration, Low or High Grade, Continued or Intermittent,\n          Highest Temp, Any Chills & Rigor.\n        * Cough, Chest Pain, dyspnoea -> RTI.\n        * Burning sensation micturition, Frequency, LAP-> UTI.\n        * Right Hypochondriac pain, Chills & Rigor-> Liver Abscess.\n        * Continued Fever & Constipation or Diarrhoea-> Typhoid fever.\n        * Joint Pain, backpain, Bodyache, Skin Rash -> Dengue/ Viral.\n        * Altered Consciousness-> Meningo-encephalitis, Malaria, Sepsis.\n        * Travel or Residence History-\n            * Haluaghat, Dhobaura, Kolmakanda, Durgapur, Sherpur, Chittagong,\n              Sylhet-> Malaria.\n            * Dhaka -> Dengue.\n\n    - Signs:\n        * Relative Bradycardia, Coated Tongue-> Typhoid Fever.\n        * Eschar Mark-> Typhus/ Rickettsial Fever.\n        * Fever+ Deep Jaundice+ Renal failure-> Leptospirosis (Common in worker\n          having prolonged contact with dirty water).\n        * Chest Features of Consolidation-> RTI.\n        * Tender Hepatomegaly-> Liver Abscess.\n        * Renal angle tender, Flank Pain->Pyelonephritis.\n        * BP< 90/60- Sepsis.\n\nProlonged Fever - Usually history is > 2 weeks:\no Common causes:\n    - Chronic Infection e.g: Tuberculosis, Infective Endocarditis, Chronic Abscess.\n    - Kala-Azar.\n    - Connective tissue disease e.g: SLE, RA, Adults Still Disease, Vasculitis.\n    - Malignancy: Lymphoma, Leukaemia.\n    - Thyrotoxicosis/ Drug Fever\n\no Clinical evaluation:\n    - Low Grade Fever, Cough, Anorexia, Weight Loss -> Tuberculosis.\n    - Residence or Travel to Muktagcha, Trishal, Fulbaria, Gofforgao, Valuka-> Kala-Azar.\n    - Joint Pain, Skin Rash, Multiorgan symptoms->SLE, RA, Adult still, Vasculitis.\n    - Lymphadenopathy, Hepato-Splenomegaly-> Lymphoma.\n    - Anaemia, Bleeding, Bony tenderness ->Leukaemia.\n    - Clubbing, Splinter Hemorrhage, Heart Murmur, Splenomegaly -> Infective Endocarditis.\n\nINVESTIGATIONS OF A PATIENT WITH FEVER\n\nIn all patient- Routines:\no CBC with ESR\no RBS\no S. Creatinine, S. electrolyes\no SGPT\no Urine R/E\no CXR P/A View\no USG W/A\n\nIf Typhoid Fever is suspected:\no 1st Week: Blood Culture.\no 2nd Week: Triple Antigen Test.\n\nIf Typhus/ Rickettsial Fever is suspected:\no Triple antigen test (usually done in 2nd week of fever)\n\nIf Leptospira is suspected:\no S. Bilirubin, S. ALP, PT\no MAT for Leptospira.\n\nIf Malaria is suspected (Altered Consciousness/ Endemic Zone/ Chills & Rigor/ Very ill patient):\no ICT for Malaria.\no Thick and Thin Film for Malaria.\n\n"}, {"title": "Typhoid Rickettsial Leptospirosis Malaria", "keywords": ["typhoid", "rickettsial", "leptospirosis", "malaria"], "content": "\nIf Dengue Fever is suspected:\no Within 4 days: Dengue NS1 Antigen.\no At 5th day: Dengue NS1 Antigen & Anti Dengue IgM, IgG.\no After 5 day: Anti Dengue IgM, IgG.\n\nIf Sepsis is suspected:\no Blood C/S, Urine C/S\no If RTI then also Sputum C/S\n\nIf Pulmonary TB is suspected:\no Sputum for AFB\no Sputum for Gene Xpert\no MT Test\n\nIf Kala-azar is suspected:\no ICT for Kala-Azar/ rK-39 Test.\no Splenic aspirate / Bone marrow examination for LD body.\n\nIf Lymphoma is suspected:\no PBF, LDH\no Lymphnode Biopsy for Histopathology\n\nIf Leukaemia is suspected:\no PBF\no Bone Marrow Study\n\nIf Adults Still is suspected:\no RA, ANA, S. Ferritin\n\nIndications of Urine C/S:\no Recurrent UTI in Female (3 or more in a year).\no Severe UTI in Male & Infant.\no Complicated UTI.\n    - UTI in Immunocompromised Patients (Pregnancy/ DM).\n    - UTI in structurally abnormal urinary tract.\no Sepsis.\n\nTreatment of a patient with Fever: According to Cause\n\nTYPHOID FEVER\n\n- Diet - 01\n- Inj. Ceftriaxone 1g (Can be switched to Cap. Cefixime 400mg BD at Discharge)\n  2 vial I/V stat & 12 Hourly for total 10-14 days.\n- Tab. Paracetamol (500mg)\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo (20mg)\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n\nRICKETTSIAL & LEPTOSPIROSIS\n\n- Cap. Doxicap 100mg (Doxycycline) [Before meal with 1 glass water in sitting position & Don't Lie\n  down with 30min]\n  1+0+1\n\nMALARIA\n\n> Uncomplicated malaria:\n    - Tab. Lumefantam/ Coartem (Artemether+Lumefantrine) [Total 24 tablets in 3 days]\n      1st day ->4 tab P/O stat & then after 8 Hours\n      2nd day-> 4+0+4\n      3rd day-> 4+0+4\n\n    Alternative Regimen:\n    - Tab. Jasoquine 300mg (Quinine sulphate)\n      2+2+2 for 7 days\n      Plus\n    - Cap Doxicap 100mg\n      1+0+1 for 7 days\n\nFor Both regimen use Gametocytocidal to reduce transmission:\n    - Tab. Jasoprim 15mg (Primaquine) / Contraindicated in Pregnancy & Child upto 6months/\n      1 tab P/O stat on Day-1\n\n> Severe Malaria/ Complicated malaria/ Unconscious or Very ill patient:\n\n    Inj. Artesunate 60mg /1 vial mixed with 1ml bicarbonate solution + 5ml N/S/\n    2 vial or 12ml I/V slowly over 4min stat & 12 hourly for 3 doses\n    then Once Daily (At least 3 Doses for Max 5 days)\n\nSwitch to oral when patient able to tolerate oral therapy:\n    Tab. Artisunate 50mg/ Artex 50\n    2+0+0 [For Total (I/V+Oral) 17-18mg/Kg]\n\nUse Gametocytocidal to reduce transmission:\n    Tab. Jasoprim 15mg (Primaquine) / Contraindicated in Pregnancy & Child upto 6months/\n    1 tab P/O stat on Day-1\n\no If Tab. Artesunate is not available, Then Use: Full Course of Tab. Lumertam or Quinine+ Doxicap as\n  in Uncomplicated Malaria.\n\n> In severe malaria if Artesunate is not available:\n\n    - Inj. Jasoquine 300mg / Quinine\n      3 ampule + Inf 5% DA 500ml\n      I/V @ 30 d/min over 4 hours stat\n      Then,\n    - Inj. Jasoquine 300mg / Quinine\n      1 1/2 ampule + Inf 5% DA 500ml\n      I/V @ 30 d/min over 4 hours 8 hourly- 6 Doses (Including Loading)\n      Then, 12 Hourly until patient can take oral Therapy\n\nSwitch to oral when patient able to tolerate oral therapy:\n    - Tab. Jasoquine 300mg (Quinine sulphate)\n      2+2+2 for 7 days\n      Plus\n    - Cap Doxicap 100mg\n      1+0+1 for 7 days\n\nUse Gametocytocidal to reduce transmission:\n    - Tab. Jasoprim 15mg (Primaquine) / Contraindicated in Pregnancy & Child upto 6months/\n      1 tab P/O stat on Day-1\n\n"}, {"title": "Tuberculosis TB", "keywords": ["tuberculosis", "tb"], "content": "\nTreatment for Tuberculosis\n\nNEWLY DIAGNOSED TB\n\n> Give category-1 anti TB drugs:\n\nIf a patient is diagnosed as a new case of pulmonary TB on 01/11/21, weight- 40kg then, Write\norder as-\n    - Tab. Rimstar 4FDC\n      3+0+0 (B/M) - for 2 months (01/11/21 to 31/12/21)\n      Then,\n    - Tab. Rimstar 2FDC\n      3+0+0 (B/M) - for next 4 months (01/01/22 to 30/04/22)\n    - Tab. Pyrovit / Sixvit 20 mg\n      0+0+1- for 6 months\n\n    o Dose of Rimstar: Number of Rimstar Tablets to be taken according to wt (kg):\n        * <37 kg -> 2 tablets\n        * 38-54 -> 3 tablets\n        * 55-70 -> 4 tablets\n        * 70 Kg -> 5 tablets\n\n    o In case of Tubercular Meningitis & spine / bone TB treatment duration will be 12\n      months (Rimstar 4FDC -> 1st 2 months, Rimstar 2FDC -> Next 10 months)\n\n> Indications of steroid with order along with anti-TB:\n\no Adrenal TB: Absolute Indication, Prolonged / lifelong Steroid supplement.\no Tubercular meningitis:\n    - Inj. Roxadex\n      1 amp I/V 6 hourly for 7 days, then\n      1 amp I/V 8 hourly for 7 days, then\n      1 amp I/V 12 hourly for 7 days, then\n    - Tab. Oradexon 0.5mg [After meal]\n      3+3+3 for next 7 days then\n      2+2+2 for next 7 days then\n      1+1+1 for next 7 days then\n      1+0+0 for next 7 days & stop\n\no Tubercular Serositis (pleural effusion, pericardial effusion, Ascitis), Extensive pulmonary\n  TB/ Miliary TB/ Life threatening TB Infection / Tubercular Laryngitis / Tubercular\n  Lymphadenitis:\n    - Tab. Cortan 10mg [After meal]\n      3+0+0 for 7 days [higher dose may be given according to weight of pt.]\n      Then, 2 1/2 +0+0 for next 7 days\n      Then, 2+0+0 for next 7 days\n      Then, 1 1/2 +0+0 for next 7 days\n      Then, 1 +0+0 for next 7 days\n      Then, 1/2 +0+0 for next 7 days & stop\n\nRETREATMENT OF TB\n\n(Treatment of patient diagnosed as pulmonary or extra pulmonary TB who got anti TB before)\n\no In those cases do Gene Xpert test in all patients.\no If Rifampicin is sensitive:\n    - Pulmonary sputum (-ve) TB:\n        * Tab. Rimstar 4 FDC for 6 months (Dose as like cat-1)\n    - Pulmonary + ve Pt or Extra pulmonary TB:\n        * Tab Rimstar 4 FDC for 6 months (Dose like cat-1)\n        Plus,\n        * Tab. Levofloxacin for 6 months (Dose-see below)\n    - Tubercular meningitis or spine / bone TB:\n        * Tab Rimstar 4 FDC for 12 months (Dose like cat-1)\n        Plus,\n        * Tab. Levofloxacin for 12 months (Dose-see below)\n\no If Rifampicin is Resistant:\n    - Treat as MDR TB.\n\no Dose of Levofloxacin (Tab. Trevox): (Tablet strength available - 250mg, 500mg, 750mg)\n    - <33 Kg -       10mg/Kg body wt once daily\n    - 33-50 Kg -     500 mg once daily\n    - 57-70 Kg -     750 mg once daily\n    - 70 Kg -        1000 mg once daily\n\n"}, {"title": "Dengue Fever", "keywords": ["dengue", "fever"], "content": "\nManagement of Dengue Fever\n\nDengue virus Infection\n    |\n    |--- Symptomatic --- Asymptomatic\n    |\n    |--- Undifferentiated fever\n    |--- Dengue Fever\n    |        |--- Without Hemorrhage\n    |        |--- With Hemorrhage --> Dengue hemorrhagic fever without shock\n    |--- Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever with plasma leakage\n    |--- Expanded Dengue Syndrome\n    |\n    Dengue with shock or Dengue shock syndrome\n\nIndications of Admission\n\no Very weak, poor appetite or Severe Dehydration.\no Presence of warning Signs or Severe Dengue Syndrome.\no Those with co-existing conditions or High Risk eg Pregnancy, Infancy, Old Age, DM, HTN, Heart\n  Failure, Renal Failure.\no Platelet Count < 100000/mm3 and Presence of Weakness, Poor appetite.\no Extreme Family Anxiety.\n\nWarning Sign\no No clinical improvement or worsening of the situation just before or during the transition to\n  afebrile phase or as the disease progresses.\no Persistent vomiting.\no Severe abdominal pain.\no Lethargy and/or restlessness, sudden behavioural changes.\no Bleeding: Epistaxis, black stool, haematemesis, excessive menstrual bleeding, dark colored urine\n  (haemoglobinuria) or haematuria.\no Giddiness.\no Pale, cold and clammy hands and feet.\no Less/no urine output for 4 - 6 hours.\no Liver enlargement > 2cm.\no Haematocrit >20%.\n\nSigns of Plasma Leakage\no Clinical:\n    * Pleural Effusion\n    * Ascitis\n    * Features Of Shock (Tachycardia, Hypotension BP< 90/60mm Hg)\no Laboratory:\n    * Hematocrit > 20% Rise from baseline\n    * Hypoalbuminaemia ( S. Albumin < 3.5 g/dl)\n\nDengue Haemorrhagic Fever\no Dengue Fever with Signs of Plasma Leakage\n\nDengue Shock Syndrome\no Dengue Shock Syndrome is a presentation of Dengue Syndromes when there is criteria of DHF\n  plus signs of circulatory failure, manifested by:\n    * Rapid and weak pulse\n    * Narrow pulse pressure (5 to 20 mm Hg)\n    * Hypotension for age\n    * Cold clammy skin\n    * Restlessness\n    * Undetectable pulse and blood pressure\n\nCompensated Shock\no Normal Systolic BP with raised Diastolic pressure eg 100/80mm Hg or 100/90mmHg\no Low Pulse Pressure (5 to 20 mm Hg)\no Postural Hypotension\n\nUncompensated Shock\no Feeble or Absent Pulse.\no Low (Systolic BP < 80/60 mm HG) or Unrecordable BP.\no Restless, Altered Consciousness.\no Oliguria/ Anuria.\n\nTourniquet test\no Inflate the cuff to a point midway between SBP and DBP, and maintain for 5 minutes.\no Reduce and wait 2 minutes.\no Then count petechiae below antecubital fossa.\no A positive test is 10 or more petechiae per 1 square inch.\n\nMANAGEMENT OF PATIENTS WITH DENGUE GROUP A\n\nDiagnostic criteria:\no Without Warning signs.\no These patients are able to tolerate adequate volumes of oral fluids.\no Pass urine at least once every six hours.\n\nThese patients may be treated at home.\n\n> Treatment:\n\nInvestigation:\no All Routines (CBC, RBS, S.\n  Creatinine, S. Electrolytes,\n  SGPT, Urine R/E, CXR P/A\n  View, ECG)\n\nIf patient comes within 1st 4 Days:\no Dengue NS1 Antigen\n\nIf patient comes on 5th day:\no Dengue NS1 Antigen and\no Anti-Dengue IgM, IgG\n  Antibody\n\nIf patient comes on 6th day or\nlater:\no Anti-Dengue IgM, IgG\n  Antibody\n\nCheck: CBC including Platelet\ncount & Hematocrit (Hct) daily.\n\nRx given:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n- Plenty of Fluid, Fruits, Fruit Juice\n    * Green coconutwater\n- Orsaline-N (1 Packet+ 500ml Water)\n  1 packet sos\n- Tab. Ace 500mg / Napa 500mg\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Avoid NSAIDs, Steroids\n- Tepid sponging\n\nMANAGEMENT OF PATIENTS WITH MODERATE DENGUE (GROUP B)\n\nDiagnostic criteria:\no With warning signs or co-morbid conditions but no features of shock.\no Needs hospital admission & close observation.\no Rapid fluid replacement is the key to prevent progression to the shock state.\n\n> Treatment:\n\nInvestigation:\no All Routines (CBC, RBS, S.\n  Creatinine, S. Electrolytes,\n  SGPT, Urine R/E, CXR P/A\n  View, ECG)\no S. Albumin, S. Calcium,\n  HCO3\n\nIf patient comes within 1st 4 Days:\no Dengue NS1 Antigen\n\nIf patient comes on 5th day:\no Dengue NS1 Antigen and\no Anti-Dengue IgM, IgG\n  Antibody\n\nIf patient comes on 6th day or\nlater:\no Anti-Dengue IgM, IgG\n  Antibody\n\nCheck: CBC including Platelet\ncount & Hematocrit (Hct) daily.\no Be careful in HF/RF and less IV fluid to be used.\n\nRx given:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n    * Plenty of Fluid, Fruits, Fruit Juice\n    * Green coconutwater\n- Orsaline-N (1 Packet+ 500ml Water)\n  (If orally can take adequately upto 1500ml daily then\n  keep IV fluid 1L daily)\n- Inf. NS 1000ml\n  I/V @ 20d/min Daily\n- Tab. Ace 500mg / Napa 500mg\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Avoid NSAIDs, Steroids\n- Tepid sponging\n- Check Pulse, BP, Urine output regularly\n\nMANAGEMENT OF PATIENTS WITH SEVERE DENGUE (GROUP C)\n\nDiagnostic criteria:\no Severe dengue that require emergency treatment and Urgent referral to ICU/HDU.\no Severe plasma leakage leading to dengue shock and/or fluid accumulation with respiratory\n  distress.\no Severe organ impairment (Hepatic damage, Renal Impairment, Myocarditis, Cardiomyopathy,\n  Encephalopathy or Encephalitis).\no Severe metabolic abnormalities (metabolic Acidosis, Severe Hypocalcaemia).\n\n> Investigations: Same as patients with Group B.\n\n> Treatment of patients with compensated shock:\n    - Same as patients with Group B (except IV fluid management)\n      Plus\n    - O2 Inhalation 4-6 L/ min sos\n    - Inf. NS 500ml\n      I/V @ 120d/min over 1 Hour\n\n    If Improved then:\n    - Inf. NS 2000ml\n      I/V@ 60d/min for 2 hour then,\n      I/V @ 30d/min for next 4 hours then,\n      I/V @ 20d/min Continue for 48 hours\n\n    If not improved with initial 500ml 5% DNS then again repeat the dose:\n    - Inf. NS 500ml\n      I/V@ 120d/min over 1 Hour\n\n    If Still not improved then Check Hct. If it is raising (or > 45%) then add Colloid as below:\n    - Inf. Plasmasol 500ml\n      I/V @ 120d/min stat\n\n    If Improved then continue fluid as like above -\n    - Inf. 5% DNS 2000ml (Use N/S in DM patients)\n      I/V@ 60d/min for 2 hour then,\n      I/V @ 30d/min for next 4 hours then,\n      I/V @ 20d/min Continue\n\n    If Not Improved Check & Correct ABCS (Acidosis, Bleeding, Calcium, Blood Sugar)\n    o Check BP, Pulse rate, Temp, R/R, Urine Output Hourly.\n    o Check Hct stat & 6 hourly (At least 12hourly).\n\n> Treatment of patients with Decompensated/ Profound Shock:\n    - Same as patients with Group B (except IV fluid management)\n      Plus\n    - O2 Inhalation\n      4-6 L/ min sos\n    - Inf. N/S 1000ml\n      I/V@ Running over 30min\n\n    If Improved then:\n    - Inf. N/S 3000ml\n      I/V@ 120d/min for 2 hour then,\n      I/V @ 60d/min for next 4 hours then,\n      I/V @ 30d/min Continue\n\n    If not improved with initial 1000ml NS then again repeat the dose:\n    - Inf. N/S 1000ml\n      I/V@ Running over 30min\n\n    If Still not improved then Check Hct. If it is raising (or > 45%) then add Colloid as below:\n    - Inf. Plasmasol 500ml\n      I/V @ 120d/min stat over 1 hour\n\n    If still not Improved, Check Hct again:\n    - If Raising Repeat Inf. Plasmasol as above.\n    - If Hct falling rapidly transfuse whole blood (10ml/kg body weight)\n\n    If Improving at any point, then continue I/V Fluid as above -\n    - Inf. N/S 3000ml\n      I/V@ 120d/min for 2 hour then,\n      I/V @ 60d/min for next 4 hours then,\n      I/V @ 30d/min Continue\n\n    If Refractory Hypotension not responding to all above measures:\n    - Check & Correct ABCS (Acidosis, Bleeding, Calcium, Blood Sugar)\n    - Use Ionotrops I/V Infusion\n    - Shift patients to ICU\n\n    o Check BP, Pulse rate, Temp, R/R, Urine Output Hourly.\n    o Check Hct stat & 6 hourly (At least 12hourly).\n    o Call to ICU for better Management.\n\nIndications for whole blood\no Hemoglobin level <= 5 gm/dl\no Significant bleeding > 10% of total blood volume (TBV). TBV of body is 80 ml/kg.\no Concealed bleeding manifested by Hct drop and unstable vital signs in spite of adequate volume\n  replacement.\n\nDose of whole fresh blood: 10 ml/kg/dose at a time.\n\nIndication for platelet concentrate\no Very severe thrombocytopenia who need urgent surgery.\no Clinical judgement of the treating physician.\n\nIf platelet concentrate is not available fresh whole blood may be transfused as per guidelines\ngiven under DHF management.\n\nDischarge Criteria\no No fever for at least 24 hours without the usage of antipyretic drugs.\no At least two days have lapsed after recovery from shock.\no Good general condition with improving appetite.\no Normal Hct at baseline value or around 38 - 40 % when baseline value is not known.\no Platelet count has risen above 50,000 /mm3.\no No distress from pleural effusions, No ascites.\no No other complications.\n\nClinical features of fluid overload in severe dengue patient\no Puffy Eye lids.\no Rapid breathing.\no Difficulty in breathing, Crepitations, wheeze, Large pleural effusions, Tense ascites, Persistent\n  abdominal Pain/ Discomfort.\n\n"}, {"title": "COVID-19", "keywords": ["covid-19"], "content": "\nManagement of COVID-19\n\nMILD COVID-19\n\nMild case: Influenza Like Illness (ILI)\nThe clinical symptoms are mild, and there is no evidence of pneumonia. Symptoms may be:\n    * Fever              * Anorexia           * Rhinorrhoea\n    * Cough              * Headache           * Sore throat\n    * Loss of taste or smell * Ageusia        * Red eye\n    * Myalgia            * Diarrhoea          * Abdominal pain\n    * Fatigue            * Vomiting             Skin lesion (chilblain, nodule)\n                                                 etc.\n\n> Treatment of mild case without comorbidities / with controlled comorbidities: (Should be\n  managed at home)\n\nInvestigation:\no rtPCR for COVID-19\no CBC\no CRP\no RBS, S. Creatinine\no CXR P/A View\no ECG (>50 yr age)\n\nRx at home:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n- Tab. Ace 500mg / Napa 500mg\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Tab. Fexo (120mg) (if rhinorrhea)\n  0+0+1\n- Syp. Ocof (if dry cough)\n  2tsf 12 hourly\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Home isolation\n\nIf patient is obese or any controlled co-morbidities present:\n    - Patient should be carefully monitored at home with\n      regular pulse oximetry and be watchful about danger\n      signs.\n\n> Treatment of mild case with multiple uncontrolled comorbid conditions: (HTN, DM, IHD, CKD,\n  CLD, COPD/Asthma/ILD and prothrombotic state such as high risk pregnancy and active malignancy\n  etc)\n\nInvestigation:\no rtPCR for COVID-19\no CBC\no CRP\no d-dimer\no S. Ferritin\no RBS, S. Creatinine, SGPT\no CXR P/A View / HRCT of\n  chest (Preferred)\no ECG (>50 yr age)\n\nRx on hospital admission:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n- Inj. Enoxaperin / Clotinex (40mg)\n  1 PFS S/C once daily\n- Tab. Moxaclav 625mg\n  1+1+1\n- Tab. Ace 500mg / Napa 500mg\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Tab. Fexo (120mg) (if rhinorrhea)\n  0+0+1\n- Syp. Ocof (if dry cough)\n  2tsf 12 hourly\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Treatment of co-morbidities (e.g: HTN/DM)\n\nMODERATE COVID-19\n\nDiagnosis of Moderate COVID-19\no Clinical signs of pneumonia\no Fever\no Cough\no Dyspnoea / Fast breathing (< 30 breaths/min)\no SpO2 >=90% but <= 93% on room air\n\n> Treatment of moderate case:\n\nInvestigation:\no rtPCR for COVID-19\no CBC\no CRP\no d-dimer\no S. Ferritin\no RBS, S. Creatinine, SGPT\no CXR P/A View / HRCT of\n  chest (Preferred)\no ECG (>50 yr age)\n\nRx on hospital admission:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n- Maintain prone position (Total 4-6 hours / day)\n- O2 inhalation (Through nasal canulla-maximum 5L/min)\n  As required to maintain SpO2>= 94%\n- Inj. Enoxaperin / Clotinex (40mg)\n  1 PFS S/C once daily (If CrCl < 30ml/min, 20mg once daily)\n- Tab. Moxaclav 625mg\n  1+1+1\n- Tab. Dexamethasone (0.5 mg)\n  4+4+4 (After meal)\n- Tab. Ace 500mg / Napa 500mg\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Tab. Fexo (120mg) (if rhinorrhea)\n  0+0+1\n- Syp. Ocof (if dry cough)\n  2tsf 12 hourly\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Treatment of co-morbidities (e.g: HTN/DM)\n\nWithin 10 days of symptom onset who needs oxygen-\n    - Inj. Remdesivir 100mg / 20ml\n      2 vial + 360ml N/S IV @ 60d/min --- Day 1\n      1 vial + 180ml N/S IV @ 60d/min --- Day 2 to Day 5\n\nSEVERE COVID-19\n\nDiagnosis of Severe COVID-19\no Clinical signs of pneumonia\no Fever\no Cough\no Severe respiratory distress (> 30 breaths/min)\no Signs of severe pneumonia (SpO2 <90% on room air)\n\n> Treatment of severe case:\n\nInvestigation:\no rtPCR for COVID-19\no CBC\no CRP\no d-dimer\no S. Ferritin\no RBS, S. Creatinine, SGPT\no CXR P/A View / HRCT of\n  chest (Preferred)\no ECG (>50 yr age)\n\nRx on hospital admission:\n- Diet - 01 (Normal)\n- Maintain prone position (Total 4-6 hours / day)\n- O2 inhalation\n  As required to maintain SpO2>= 94%\n- Inj. Enoxaperin / Clotinex (60mg)\n  1 PFS S/C once daily (If CrCl < 30ml/min, 20mg once daily)\n- Inj. Remdesivir 100mg / 20ml (within 10 days of\n  symptom onset)\n  2 vial + 360ml N/S IV @ 60d/min --- Day 1\n  1 vial + 180ml N/S IV @ 60d/min --- Day 2 to Day 5\n- Inj. Moxaclav 1.2gm (Inj. Meropenem in critical cases)\n  1 vial IV stat and TDS\n- Inj. Dexamethasone (6 mg)\n  1 amp. IV stat and daily\n- Tab. Ace 500mg / Napa 500mg\n  2+2+2 (After meal)\n- Tab. Fexo (120mg) (if rhinorrhea)\n  0+0+1\n- Syp. Ocof (if dry cough)\n  2tsf 12 hourly\n- Cap. Omeprazole /Seclo 20mg\n  1+0+1 (Before meal)\n- Treatment of co-morbidities (e.g: HTN/DM)\n\nOxygen therapy: Escalate oxygen flow as per patient's SpO2 and degree of respiratory distress. Change\nof oxygen delivery device as required to maintain SpO2:\n- Nasal cannula (up to 5 litre), Oxygen mask (6-10 litre) and Non-Rebreather bag with reservoir\n  bag (10-15 litre).\n- We recommend immediate administration of supplemental oxygen to any patient with\n  emergency signs during resuscitation to target SpO2>= 94% and to any patient\n  without emergency signs and hypoxaemia (i.e. stable hypoxaemic patient) to target SpO2> 90%\n  or >= 92-95% in pregnant women.\n\nTocilizumab\n\nIndication: It should not be routinely used to manage severe to critical COVID-19. It can only be used\nunder consultant's supervision only if following clinical and biochemical criteria are fulfilled:\n\no Clinical Criteria:\n  Patients (Adult >=18 years) who have been admitted to the intensive care unit (ICU) within the\n  last 24 hours and who require invasive mechanical ventilation, noninvasive mechanical\n  ventilation (NIV), or high flow nasal canula (HFNC) oxygen (needing >30 L/min of oxygen and\n  FiO2>0.4\n\no Biochemical criteria:\n  CRP> 75 mg/dL\n\nDosing:\no Consider only 1 dose at 8 mg/kg (max: 800 mg/dose). Can be repeated after 12-24 hours if no\n  clinical improvement. Max 2 doses.\n\nContraindication:\no Significant immunosuppression, particularly in those with a history of recent use of other\n  biologics.\no Immunemodulating drugs.\no Alanine transaminase (ALT) >5 times the upper limit of normal.\no High risk for gastrointestinal perforation.\no An uncontrolled, serious bacterial, fungal, or non-SARS-CoV-2 viral infection.\no Absolute neutrophil count <500 cells/uL.\no Platelet count <50,000 cells/uL.\n\nAdmission criteria\n\nAll suspected/ confirmed cases of COVID-19 presenting as:\no Moderate case: clinical or radiological evidence of pneumonia.\no Severe case: clinical or radiological evidence of pneumonia with signs of severe pneumonia\n  (RR > 30 /min or oxygen saturation <90%)\no Critical COVID-19: ARDS, Sepsis, Septic shock\no Hypoxia (SPO2<=93%) even in the absence of any clinical signs\no Patient with multiple uncontrolled comorbidities or prothrombotic state such as high-risk\n  pregnancy, active malignancy, DVT irrespective of severity etc.\n\nDischarge criteria\n\no Resolution of fever without the use of anti-pyretics such as paracetamol and significant\n  improvement in the respiratory symptoms (e.g., cough, shortness of breath) for at least 03\n  days.\no For severe or critical patients: physician's discretion may be used for giving discharge.\no There is no need for retesting the patient to give discharge from hospital.\n\n"}];
